# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-rome
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] An institutional referendum (Italian: *referendum istituzionale*, or *referendum sulla forma istituzionale dello Stato*) was held by universal suffrage in the Kingdom of Italy on 2 June 1946, a key event of contemporary Italian history.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Until 1946, Italy was a kingdom ruled by the House of Savoy, reigning since the unification of Italy in 1861 and previously rulers of the Kingdom of Sardinia.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1922, the rise of Benito Mussolini and the creation of the Fascist regime in Italy, which eventually resulted in engaging the country in World War II alongside Nazi Germany, considerably weakened the role of the royal house.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Following the Italian Civil War and the Liberation of Italy from Axis troops in 1945, a popular referendum on the institutional form of the state was called the next year and resulted in voters choosing the replacement of the monarchy with a republic.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The 1946 Italian general election to elect the Constituent Assembly of Italy was held on the same day.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] As with the simultaneous Constituent Assembly elections, the referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The results were proclaimed by the Supreme Court of Cassation on 10 June 1946: 12,717,923 citizens in favor of the republic and 10,719,284 citizens in favor of the monarchy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The event is commemorated annually by the *Festa della Repubblica*.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the entry into force of the new Constitution of the Italian Republic, on 1 January 1948, Enrico De Nicola became the first to assume the functions of president of Italy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It marked the first time that most of the Italian Peninsula was under a single republican government since the fall of the Roman Republic.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the history of Italy there are several so-called "republican" governments that have followed one another over time.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Examples are the ancient Roman Republic and the medieval maritime republics.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From Cicero to Niccolò Machiavelli, Italian philosophers have imagined the foundations of political science and republicanism.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But it was Giuseppe Mazzini who revived the republican idea in Italy in the 19th century.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] An Italian nationalist in the historical radical tradition and a proponent of a republicanism of social-democratic inspiration, Mazzini helped define the modern European movement for popular democracy in a republican state.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Mazzini formulated a concept known as "thought and action" in which thought and action must be joined and every thought must be followed by action, therefore rejecting intellectualism and the notion of divorcing theory from practice.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The foundation of the Young Italy constitutes a key moment of the Italian Risorgimento and this republican program precedes in time the proposals for the unification of Italy of Vincenzo Gioberti and Cesare Balbo, aimed at reunifying the Italian territory under the presidency of the Pope.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Subsequently, the philosopher Carlo Cattaneo promoted a secular and republican Italy in the extension of Mazzini's ideas, but organized as a federal republic.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The political projects of Mazzini and Cattaneo were thwarted by the action of the Piedmontese Prime Minister Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, and Giuseppe Garibaldi.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The latter set aside his republican ideas to favor Italian unity.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After having obtained the conquest of the whole of southern Italy during the Expedition of the Thousand, Garibaldi handed over the conquered territories to the king of Sardinia Victor Emmanuel II, which were annexed to the Kingdom of Sardinia after a plebiscite.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This earned him heavy criticism from numerous republicans who accused him of treason.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] While a laborious administrative unification began, a first Italian parliament was elected and, on 17 March 1861, Victor Emmanuel II was proclaimed king of Italy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From 1861 to 1946, Italy was a constitutional monarchy founded on the Albertine Statute, named after the king who promulgated it in 1848, Charles Albert of Sardinia.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The parliament included a Senate, whose members were appointed by the king, and a Chamber of Deputies, elected by census vote.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1861 only 2% of Italians had the right to vote.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the political panorama of the time there was a republican political movement which had its martyrs, such as the soldier Pietro Barsanti.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Barsanti was a supporter of republican ideas, and was a soldier in the Royal Italian Army with the rank of corporal.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He was sentenced to death and shot in 1870 for having favored an insurrectional attempt against the Savoy monarchy and is therefore considered the first martyr of the modern Italian Republic and a symbol of republican ideals in Italy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The balance of power between the Chamber and Senate initially shifted in favor of the Senate, composed mainly of nobles and industrial figures.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Little by little, the Chamber of Deputies took on more and more importance with the evolution of the bourgeoisie and the large landowners, concerned with economic progress, but supporters of order and a certain social conservatism.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republicans took part in the elections to the Italian Parliament, and in 1853 they formed the Action Party around Giuseppe Mazzini.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although in exile, Mazzini was elected in 1866, but refused to take his seat in parliament.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Carlo Cattaneo was elected deputy in 1860 and 1867, but refused so as not to have to swear loyalty to the House of Savoy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The problem of the oath of loyalty to the monarchy, necessary to be elected, was the subject of controversy within the republican forces.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1873 Felice Cavallotti, one of the most committed Italian politicians against the monarchy, preceded his oath with a declaration in which he reaffirmed his republican beliefs.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1882, a new electoral law lowered the census limit for voting rights, increasing the number of voters to over two million, equal to 7% of the population.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the same year the Italian Workers' Party was created, which in 1895 became the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1895 the intransigent republicans agreed to participate in the political life of the Kingdom, establishing the Italian Republican Party.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two years later, the far left reached its historical maximum level in Parliament with 81 deputies, for the three radical-democratic, socialist components and Republican.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the death of Felice Cavallotti in 1898, the radical left gave up on posing the institutional problem.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In Italian politics, the socialist party progressively divided into two tendencies: a maximalist one, led among others by Arturo Labriola and Enrico Ferri, and supporting the use of strikes; the other, reformist and pro-government, was led by Filippo Turati.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A nationalist movement emerged, led in particular by Enrico Corradini, as well as a Catholic social and democratic movement, the National Democratic League, led by Romolo Murri.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1904, Pope Pius X authorized Catholics to participate individually in political life, but in 1909 he condemned the National Democratic League created by Romolo Murri, who was excommunicated.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Finally, a law of 3 June 1912 marked Italy's evolution towards a certain political liberalism by establishing universal male suffrage.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Italy began to be counted among the world's liberal democracies.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After World War I, Italian political life was animated by four great movements.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two of these movements were in favor of democratic development within the framework of existing monarchical institutions: the reformist socialists and the Italian People's Party.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Two other movements challenged these institutions: the Republican Party on the one hand, and the maximalist socialists.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the 1919 elections, the parties most imbued with republican ideology (the maximalist socialists and the Republican Party) won, obtaining 165 out of 508 seats in the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the 1921 elections, after the foundation of the Italian Communist Party, the three parties republican, maximalist socialist and communist obtained 145 deputies out of 535.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Overall, at the beginning of the interwar period, less than 30% of those elected were in favor of the establishment of a republican regime.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In this context, the rise of Benito Mussolini's fascist movement was based on the bitterness generated by the "mutilated victory", the fear of social unrest and the rejection of revolutionary, republican and Marxist ideology.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The liberal political system and part of the aristocracy chose to erect fascism as a bulwark against, in their way of seeing, these dangers.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In October 1922, the nomination of Benito Mussolini as prime minister by King Victor Emmanuel III, following the march on Rome, paved the way for the establishment of the dictatorship.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Albertine Statute was progressively emptied of its content.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Parliament was subject to the will of the new government.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 27 June 1924, 127 deputies left Parliament and retreated to the Aventine Hill, a clumsy maneuver which, in effect, left the field open to the fascists.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] They then had the fate of Italy in their hands for two decades.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Not only did Victor Emmanuel III appeal to Mussolini to form the government in 1922 and allow him to proceed with the domestication of Parliament, but he did not even draw the consequences of the assassination of Giacomo Matteotti in 1924.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He accepted the title of emperor in 1936 at the end of Second Italo-Ethiopian War, then the alliance with Nazi Germany and Italy's entry into World War II on 10 June 1940.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] With the implementation of fascist laws (Royal Decree of 6 November 1926), all political parties operating on Italian territory were dissolved, with the exception of the National Fascist Party.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some of these parties expatriated and reconstituted themselves abroad, especially in France.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some movements remained outside, including the Italian Communist Party, the popular Catholic movement and other liberal movements.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This coalition dissolved on 5 May 1934 and, in August of the same year, the pact of unity of action was signed between the Italian Socialist Party and the Italian Communist Party.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the meantime, in Italy, clandestine anti-fascist nuclei were formed, in particular in Milan with Ferruccio Parri and in Florence with Riccardo Bauer.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Under the impetus of these groups, the Action Party, Mazzini's former republican party, was re-established.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Between the end of 1942 and the beginning of 1943, Alcide De Gasperi wrote *The reconstructive ideas of Christian Democracy*, which laid the foundations of the new Catholic-inspired party, the Christian Democracy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It brought together the veterans of Luigi Sturzo's Italian People's Party and the young people of Catholic associations, in particular of the University Federation.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 10 July 1943, the Allies landed in Sicily in Operation Husky.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 25 July 1943, Victor Emmanuel III revoked Mussolini's mandate as prime minister and had him arrested, entrusting the government to Marshal Pietro Badoglio.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The new government contacted the Allies to reach an armistice.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] When the Armistice of Cassibile was announced on 8 September 1943, the Germans reacted by placing under their control all the part of Italian territory that still escaped the Allied advance and by disarming the Italian Royal Army.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Victor Emmanuel III and Badoglio's government fled Rome and reached Brindisi, in southern Italy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In these dramatic circumstances, in the two territories the civil administration gave way to a military and police administration.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the parties that existed before fascism were reconstituted, alongside new political parties.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 9 September 1943, in Rome (still occupied by the Germans), a National Liberation Committee (CLN) was created, which brought together the parties and movements opposed to fascism and German occupation.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It was made up of representatives of the Italian Communist Party, members of the Action Party, Christian Democrats, liberals, socialists and progressive democrats.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The patriotic war of liberation led by the National Liberation Committee was also, for a significant part of its supporters, a war of social liberation, a war against a collaborationist elite.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the Americans and English, anxious to prepare for the post-war period, facilitated the entry into German-occupied territory of Italian democratic and republican activists aimed at counterbalancing the communist influence in the leadership of the National Liberation Committee.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This was the case, for example, of Leo Valiani, future member of the triumvirate responsible for the partisan insurrection in Piedmont and Lombardy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 31 March 1944, in Salerno, Palmiro Togliatti, general secretary of the Italian Communist Party, called for the formation of a government of national unity and no longer required the king's abdication as a prerequisite.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This declaration pushed the parties of the National Liberation Committee to rally around a compromise drawn up by Enrico De Nicola, president of the Chamber of Deputies until 1924, by Benedetto Croce of the liberal party and by the king's entourage.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] As foreseen in this agreement, upon the liberation of Rome, on 4 June 1944, Victor Emmanuel III proclaimed his son Umberto lieutenant general of the kingdom, and the parties took political control of the nation, even if the war continued, stabilizing on the front on the Gothic line until April 1945.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] From June 1944 to December 1945, three provisional coalition governments followed one another.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The first was led by Ivanoe Bonomi, of the Labour Democratic Party.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] His government included the anti-fascist liberals Carlo Sforza and Benedetto Croce, as well as Palmiro Togliatti.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although temporarily put aside, the question of Italian institutions remained one of the main open political questions.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Most of the forces supporting the National Liberation Committee were openly republicans and believed that the monarchy, in particular Victor Emmanuel III, had had a responsibility in the success of the fascist movement.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The final agreement between the parties was to ask that at the end of the war, as soon as conditions were favourable, the calling of elections, an institutional referendum and the formation of a constituent assembly.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Until then, on 31 January 1945, the Council of Ministers, chaired by Ivanoe Bonomi, issued a decree which recognized women's right to vote.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Universal suffrage was thus recognized, after the vain attempts made in 1881 and 1907 by women of the various parties.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Bonomi governments (II then III) were succeeded by the Parri government in June 1945, then by the First De Gasperi government in December 1945.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The question of the future form of the state, monarchy or republic, absorbed the minds of political circles.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The majority of Christian Democratic activists, especially young people, increasingly distanced themselves from the monarchy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] During the local meetings of the leaders of this party, in Rome and Milan, motions were presented aimed at making official a political line favorable to a democratic republic.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The central political office tried to curb these pressures and maintain an intermediate position.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 16 March 1946, Prince Umberto decreed, as expected in 1944, that the question of the institutional form of the state would be decided by a referendum organized simultaneously with the election of a constituent assembly.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation was responsible for examining the appeals.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Its role was to be limited to observing the progress of voting operations and consolidating the bulletins issued by the offices that communicated the results in each constituency.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The counting of the ballots of the candidates for the constituent assembly had to precede that of the referendum.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] If the monarchy had won, it would have been the Constituent Assembly that would have had to choose the head of state.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Wanted by the Allies to verify that the conditions existed for voting in a country torn apart by the civil war only a few months earlier, partial municipal and provincial elections were held in March and April 1946 in half of the Italian municipalities and provinces.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] These elections, which mainly involved left-wing cities, brought out three parties, with a clear advantage for the Christian Democrats, led by Alcide De Gasperi, which exceeded the sum of votes cast for the Italian Communist Party and the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After these administrative elections, the monarchists, already worried about the outcome of the referendum, became even more discouraged.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But a political event changed the situation during the referendum campaign.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A month before the referendum, Victor Emmanuel III abdicated in favor of his son Umberto, who was proclaimed king and took the name Umberto II.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The act of abdication, drawn up privately, is dated 9 May 1946.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This abdication was desired by the monarchists, since the crown prince was less compromised than his father in Mussolini's rise to power and in coexistence with the fascist forces.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It is also possible that the command of the allied forces present on Italian territory encouraged the sovereign to abdicate in favor of his son.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The former king immediately left Italy for Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Umberto II confirmed his promise to respect the popular decision regarding the referendum.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The representatives of the parties in favor of the Republic protested, arguing the assumption of royal powers by the lieutenant general conflicted with an article of the legislative decree of 16 March 1946 that aimed at guaranteeing institutional stability before the announcement of the results.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] For observers, the gap between republicans and monarchists was narrowing, which increased tension in the final phase of the electoral campaign.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In fact, some scuffles broke out between activists of the two sides in the tense climate.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The vote for the choice between monarchy or republic took place on 2 June and on the morning of 3 June 1946.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the transfer of the electoral cards from all of Italy and the minutes of the 31 constituencies to Rome, the results were expected on 8 June.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 10 June, the still provisional results were announced, and the final ones were communicated later due to missing data in some polling stations and after the examination of numerous appeals regarding the contested referendum ballots.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In fact, 21,000 disputes occurred over the referendum ballots, most of which were quickly resolved.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, the period of uncertainty between the end of the vote and the final official announcement of the results only strengthened tensions in the country.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the city of Naples, in Apulia, in Calabria and in Sicily, the monarchists carried out protest demonstrations, sometimes violent.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 7 June, a monarchist student, soon transformed into a martyr, was killed.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] One of the complaints submitted to the Supreme Court of Cassation is particularly delicate.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This controversy was over the definition of "majority".
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The monarchists believed that it was necessary to take into account not the majority of votes cast, but the "majority of electors", as an article of the electoral law provided.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The public prosecutor of the Supreme Court of Cassation, Massimo Pilotti, deemed this appeal admissible.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In his indictment Pilotti believed that the spirit and letter of the decrees as well as jurisprudence provide for the counting of voters, without excluding blank or invalid ballots.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But the Supreme Court of Cassation ruled against him, with 12 votes against to 7.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the one hand, it was believed that the vote, as a legal act, manifested a will and that the blank or null vote could be assimilated to the absence of expression of will.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation also identified another decree which specified that only "validly cast" votes should be preserved.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation finally announced that no law or decree dealt with the need for an absolute majority.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The final results were announced on 18 June 1946.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Voter turnout was 89%, with 54% of the votes cast for the republic and 46% for the monarchy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The analysis of the data by region showed an Italy practically divided in two: in the north the republic won with 66% of the votes cast, and the monarchy in the south with 64% of the votes.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] However, some voters were unable to vote.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Before the closure of the electoral lists in April 1945, many Italian soldiers were still outside the national territory, in detention or internment camps abroad.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] These provinces, however, were all located in the north of the country, an area where the Republican vote obtained a fairly large majority.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The conservative, rural *Mezzogiorno* (southern Italy) region voted solidly for the monarchy (63.8%) while the more urbanised and industrialised *Nord* (northern Italy) voted equally firmly for a republic (66.2%).
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] At first glance, the referendum seemed to simply divide Italy in two, between North and South, but the situation was more complex.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] For example, the districts located to the north of Rome gave the majority to the republic, while those located to the south chose the monarchy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The electoral college of Rome was very divided and gave a slight majority to the choice of the monarchic regime.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republican choice turned into a plebiscite, with over 80% of the votes cast in the electoral college of Bologna, and even more in that of Trento.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the South, however, the monarchist choice reached nearly 80% in the college of Naples.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] But, in other regions, the vote was very fragmented.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] There was not a total break with the past, but an interference between the two possible choices, which was expressed everywhere.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The occupation of the North by the German forces and the period of the Italian Civil War, with the fascist forces, undoubtedly favored an increase in the importance of the socialist and communist parties in this region, which were republican in tendency.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] During these dark years, the populations concerned placed part of their hopes in dreams of revolution, or at least of change.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The South, not having experienced this situation and having welcomed King Victor Emmanuel III and his government, was perhaps more wary of these parties and placed its trust in the monarchic regime, preferring continuity to the "leap into the unknown" represented by the republican form.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Furthermore, the clientelism prevalent in the South favored a vote that tended to be conservative, and therefore monarchist.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Some analysts also cite the influence of the Catholic Church or the Catholic press.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Other authors have highlighted more structural factors, such as differences in family organization or production by region.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Thus Carlo Bacetti compared, in Tuscany, the importance of metayage in the organization of work on the land, and the weight of the Communist Party in this region, which had republican tendencies.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] At the same time, republican demonstrations took place in many cities.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Milanese newspaper, *Corriere della Sera*, on Tuesday 11 June, ran the headline: "The Italian Republic is born".
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] *La Stampa*, a Turin daily newspaper, declared more soberly: "The government confirms the victory of the republicans", and completed its coverage by asking: "the question is whether the republic has been proclaimed or not".
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In Naples, a city with a population largely supportive of the monarchy, an incident occurred on 11 June.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] A procession of supporters of the monarchy advanced towards the municipal buildings and then changed objective and headed towards the headquarters of the Italian Communist Party.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The crowd saw a red flag, but also a tricolor flag from which the royal coat of arms had been cut.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Despite the presence of armored vehicles, the demonstrators attempted to storm the communist party headquarters.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Protesters and law enforcement officers exchange gunfire.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] According to the prefect's report, the demonstrators shot first.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In any case the response was deadly, with machine gun fire.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] There were nine deaths among royalist demonstrators and a large number of injuries.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Calm returned to the city only on 13 June.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the night of 12 June, the government met at Alcide De Gasperi's invitation.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Prime Minister received a written communication from the King, in which he said he was ready to respect the verdict of the electors' vote, but adding that he would await the final declaration of the Supreme Court of Cassation.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The letter and the protests of the monarchists, like the bloody events of the day before in Naples, as well as the new demonstrations announced by the monarchists worried the ministers.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Prime Minister collected all the votes of the government members, with the exception of the liberal minister Leone Cattani.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Although some members of his entourage encouraged him to oppose this decision, the king, informed, decided to leave the country the following day, thus making a peaceful transfer of power possible, not without having denounced De Gasperi's "revolutionary gesture".
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He went into exile in Cascais, Portugal.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the same day as the former king's departure, the flag of Italy with the Savoy coat of arms in the centre was lowered from the Quirinal Palace.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Italian flag was modified with the decree of the president of the Council of Ministers No.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Compared to the monarchic banner, the Savoy coat of arms was eliminated.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The Republican tricolour was then officially and solemnly delivered to the Italian military corps on 4 November 1947 on the occasion of National Unity and Armed Forces Day.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The universally adopted ratio is 2:3, while the war flag is squared (1:1).
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Each *comune* also has a *gonfalone* bearing its coat of arms.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 27 May 1949, a law was passed that described and regulated the way the flag was displayed outside public buildings and during national holidays.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the birth of the Italian Republic, "La leggenda del Piave" was temporarily chosen as the provisional national anthem, which replaced "Marcia Reale", the national anthem of the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The political class of the time then approved the proposal of the War Minister Cipriano Facchinetti, who foresaw the adoption of "Il Canto degli Italiani" as a provisional anthem of the State.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] "Il Canto degli Italiani" was therefore chosen, on 12 October 1946, as the provisional national anthem, a role that it later preserved while remaining the de facto anthem of the Italian Republic.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Over the decades there were several unsuccessful attempts to make it the official national anthem, until it finally gained official status on 4 December 2017.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 18 June 1946 at 6 pm, in the Sala della Lupa of Palazzo Montecitorio in Rome, the Supreme Court of Cassation proceeded to proclaim the results of the referendum, without accompanying this formalization with reservations as it had done previously.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In the first session of the Constituent Assembly, on 28 June 1946, Enrico De Nicola was elected provisional head of the State, in the first round with 396 votes out of 501.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] In addition to his personal qualities, the choice of a man born in Naples and long monarchic history, it was a sign of pacification and union towards the populations of southern Italy, in this accelerated transition towards the Republic.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] He was initially only provisional head of state and not president of Italy, since the latter did not yet have a constitution.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Alcide De Gasperi resigned and then regained the task of forming a new government, thus becoming the last Prime Minister of the monarchic era and the first of republican Italy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On 1 January 1948, the Republican Constitution came into force, the content of which was discussed within the Constituent Assembly.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It proclaims in particular that "Italy is a democratic republic founded on labour" and that "the former kings of the House of Savoy, their wives and their male descendants are prohibited from entering and staying in the national territory".
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Enrico De Nicola then assumed the title of President of Italy.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The validity of the provision that prohibited the entry in Italy of some members of the House of Savoy ceased with the entry into force of the Constitutional Law of 23 October 2002, No.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] 1, after a debate in parliament and in the country that lasted many years and Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples, son of King Umberto II, was able to enter Italy with his family already in the following December for a short visit.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The former queen Marie-José had already been authorized to return to Italy in 1987 since, with the death of her husband Umberto II and having become a widow, her status as "spouse" was recognized as having ceased.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The photo, which later became a "symbol" of the celebrations for the outcome of the referendum, portrays the face of a young woman emerging from a copy of *Il Corriere della Sera* of 6 June 1946 with the title «*È nata la Repubblica Italiana*» ("The Italian Republic is born").
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The symbolic photo of the birth of the Republic was taken by Federico Patellani for the weekly *Tempo* (n.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] 22, 15–22 June 1946) as part of a photo shoot celebrating the Republic and the new role of women; it was also featured on the front page of the *Il Corriere della Sera* itself and was later reused in many campaigns and posters.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Only in 2016 was the woman identified as Anna Iberti (1922–1997).
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] After the playing of the National Anthem *Il Canto degli Italiani*, the Frecce Tricolori cross the skies of Rome.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] It is tradition, for the members of the Italian government and for the presidents of the two chambers of parliament, to have pinned on their jacket, during the whole ceremony, an Italian tricolor cockade.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Following the anthem, the military parade begins, which the ground columns of military personnel saluting the President with eyes left or right with their colours dipped as they march past the dais.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Mobile column crew contingent colour guards perform the salute in a like manner.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] The military parade also includes some military delegations from the United Nations, NATO, the European Union and representatives of multinational departments with an Italian component.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] On the holiday, at the Quirinale Palace, the Changing of the Guard with the Corazzieri Regiment and the Fanfare of the Carabinieri Cavalry Regiment in high uniform is carried out in solemn form.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] This solemn rite is only performed on two other occasions, during the celebrations of the Tricolour Day (7 January) and the National Unity and Armed Forces Day (4 November).
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Official ceremonies are held throughout the national territory.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Among them are the traditional receptions organized by each prefecture for the local authorities, which are preceded by solemn public demonstrations with reduced military parades that have been reviewed by the prefect in his capacity as the highest governmental authority in the province.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Similar ceremonies are also organized by the Regions and Municipalities.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] All over the world, Italian embassies organize ceremonies to which the Heads of State of the host country are invited.
[src:ancient-rome/1946-italian-institutional-referendum] Greetings from the other Heads of State reach the President of Italy from all over the world.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The **2015 European migrant crisis** was a period of significantly increased movement of refugees and migrants into Europe, mostly from the Middle East.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] An estimated 1.3 million people came to the continent to request asylum, the most in a single year since World War II.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] They were mostly Syrians, but also included a significant number of people from Afghanistan, Pakistan, Iraq, Nigeria, Eritrea, and the Balkans.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The increase in asylum seekers has been attributed to factors such as the escalation of various wars in the Middle East and ISIL's territorial and military dominance in the region due to the Arab Winter, as well as Lebanon, Jordan, and Egypt ceasing to accept Syrian asylum seekers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The EU attempted to enact some measures to address the problem, including distributing refugees among member countries, tackling root causes of emigration in the home countries of migrants, and simplifying deportation processes.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] However, attempts to coordinate an EU-wide response largely failed, as most countries refused to accept large numbers of migrants, and several refused to take in any at all.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Many European Union (EU) governments closed their borders.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Germany ultimately accepted most of the refugees after the government decided to temporarily suspend its enforcement of the Dublin Regulation.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Germany would receive over 440,000 asylum applications (0.5% of the population).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Other countries that took in a significant number of refugees include Sweden (156,000; 1.6%) and Austria (88,000; 1.0%).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Hungary also initially registered 174,000 applications, but most of these were withdrawn or canceled.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The crisis had significant political consequences in Europe.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The influx of migrants caused significant demographic and cultural changes within these countries.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] As a consequence, some politicians raised concerns about the challenges of integrating migrants, and the public raised discussions about potential effects to European values.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Paired also with rising cost of living and other complex social problems, political polarization increased, confidence in the European Union fell, and many countries implemented stricter asylum policies.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Right-wing populist parties gained support as immigration became a key political issue and became significantly more popular in many countries.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] There was an increase in protests regarding immigration and the circulation of the white nationalist conspiracy theory of the Great Replacement.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] News organisations and academic sources use both *migrant crisis* and *refugee crisis* to refer to the 2015 events, sometimes interchangeably.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Some argued that the word *migrant* was pejorative or inaccurate in the context of people fleeing war and persecution because it implies most are emigrating voluntarily rather than being forced to leave their homes.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The BBC and *The Washington Post* argued against the stigmatization of the word, contending that it simply refers to anyone moving from one country to another.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The most significant root cause of the wave of refugees entering Europe in 2015 was the Syrian civil war.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Several other countries in the Middle East and northern Africa were also experiencing social unrest that drove people to flee.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In 2014, the EU member states counted around 252,000 irregular arrivals and 626,065 asylum applications, the highest number since the 672,000 applications received in the wake of the Yugoslav Wars in 1992.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Four countries – Germany, Sweden, Italy and France – received around two-thirds of the EU's asylum applications.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Sweden, Hungary and Austria were among the top recipients of EU asylum applications *per capita*, when adjusted for their own populations, with 8.4 asylum seekers per 1,000 inhabitants in Sweden, 4.3 in Hungary, and 3.2 in Austria.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The EU countries that hosted the largest numbers of refugees at the end of 2014 were France (252,000), Germany (217,000), Sweden (142,000) and the United Kingdom (117,000).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In 2014, the main countries of origin, accounting for almost half of the asylum seekers, were Syria (20%), Afghanistan (7%), Eritrea (6%), Kosovo (6%) and Albania.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Most crossed the Mediterranean Sea from Libya.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The overall rate of recognition of asylum applicants was 45 per cent at the first instance and 18 per cent on appeal although there were huge differences between EU states, ranging from Hungary (accepted 9% of applicants) to Sweden (accepted 74%).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] According to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, most of the people who arrived in Europe in 2015 were refugees fleeing war and persecution in Syria, Afghanistan, Iraq and Eritrea: 84% of Mediterranean Sea arrivals in 2015 came from the world's top ten refugee-producing countries.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Wars fueling the migrant crisis were the Syrian Civil War, the Iraq War, the War in Afghanistan, the War in Somalia, and the War in Darfur.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Refugees from Eritrea, one of the most repressive states in the world, fled from indefinite military conscription and forced labour.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Migration from Kosovo occurred in phases beginning from the second half of the 20th century.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The Kosovo War (February 1998 – June 1999) created a wave.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] On 19 May 2011, Kosovo established the Ministry of Diaspora.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Kosovo also established the Kosovo Diaspora Agency (KDA) to support migrants.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The unemployment rate in Kosovo in 2014 was estimated at 30%, a majority of the unemployed being in the age range 15–24.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] This was reflected in the age range of the emigrants, roughly 50% of whom were youth between the age of 15–24.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Detected illegal border crossings to the EU from Kosovo numbered 22,069 in 2014 and 23,793 in 2015.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The anti-government protests of 2015 coincided with a surge in migrant numbers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The Syrian civil war began in response to the Arab Spring protests of March 2011, which quickly escalated into a civil uprising.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] By May 2011, thousands of people had fled the country and the first refugee camps opened in Turkey.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In March 2012, the UNHCR appointed a Regional Coordinator for Syrian Refugees, recognising the growing concerns surrounding the crisis.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] As the conflict descended into full civil war, outside powers, notably Iran, Turkey, the United States and Russia funded and armed different sides of the conflict and sometimes intervened directly.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] By March 2013, the total number of Syrian refugees reached 1,000,000, the vast majority of whom were internally displaced within Syria or had fled to Turkey or Lebanon; smaller numbers had sought refuge in Iraq and Egypt.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Afghan refugees constitute the second-largest refugee population in the world.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] According to the UNHCR, there are almost 2.5 million registered refugees from Afghanistan.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Most of these refugees fled the region due to war and persecution.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The majority have resettled in Pakistan and Iran, though it became increasingly common to migrate further west to the European Union.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Afghanistan faced over 40 years of conflict dating back to the Soviet invasion in 1979.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Since then, the nation faced fluctuating levels of civil war amidst unending unrest.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The increase in refugee numbers was primarily attributed to the Taliban presence within Afghanistan.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Their retreat in 2001 led to nearly 6 million Afghan refugees returning to their homeland.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] However, after the Taliban insurgency against NATO-led forces and subsequent Fall of Kabul, nearly 2.5 million refugees fled Afghanistan.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The Boko Haram insurgency in Nigeria has resulted in the deaths of 20,000 people and displaced at least 2 million since 2009.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Around 75,000 Nigerians requested asylum in the EU in 2015 and 2016, around 3 per cent of the total.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In all, over 1 million refugees and migrants crossed the Mediterranean (mostly the Aegean Sea) in 2015, three to four times more than the previous year.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] 80% were fleeing from wars in Syria, Iraq, and Afghanistan.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] About 85% of sea arrivals were in Greece (via Turkey) and 15% in Italy (via northern Africa).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The European Union's external land borders (e.g., in Greece, Bulgaria or Finland) played only a minor role.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Some also crossed via the Central Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] This path is a much longer and considerably more dangerous journey than the relatively short trip across the Aegean.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] As a result, this route was responsible for a large majority of migrant deaths in 2015, even though it was far less used.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] An estimated 2,889 died in the Central Mediterranean; 731 died in the Aegean sea.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The EU Border and Coast Guard Agency (Frontex) uses the terms "illegal" and "irregular" border crossings for crossings of an EU external border but not at an official border-crossing point.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Because many migrants cross more than one external EU border (for instance when traveling through the Balkans from Greece to Hungary), the total number of irregular EU external border crossings is often higher than the number of irregular migrants arriving in the EU in a year.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] News media sometimes misrepresent these figures as given by Frontex.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Because the refugees entering Europe in 2015 were predominantly from the Middle East, the vast majority first entered the EU by crossing the Aegean Sea from Turkey to Greece by boat; Turkey's land border has been inaccessible to migrants since a border fence was constructed there in 2012.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A number of Greek islands are less than 6 km (4 mi) from the Turkish coast, such as Chios, Kos, Lesbos, Leros, Kastellorizo, Agathonisi, Farmakonisi, Rhodes, Samos and Symi.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] At one point, incoming refugees on some of these islands outnumbered locals.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A small number of people (34,000 or 3% of the total) used Turkey's land borders with Greece or Bulgaria.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] From Greece, most tried to make their way toward through the Balkans to Central and Northern Europe.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] This represented a stark change to the previous year, when most refugees and migrants landed in Italy from northern Africa.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In fact, in the first half of 2015, Italy was, as in previous years, the most common landing point for refugees entering the EU, especially the southern Sicilian island of Lampedusa.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] By June, however, Greece overtook Italy in the number of arrivals and became the starting point of a flow of refugees and migrants moving through Balkan countries to Northern European countries, particularly Germany and Sweden.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] By the end of 2015, about 80% of migrants had landed in Greece, compared to only 15% in Italy.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Greece appealed to the European Union for assistance; the UNCHR European Director Vincent Cochetel said facilities for migrants on the Greek islands were "totally inadequate" and the islands were in "total chaos".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Frontex's Operation Poseidon, aimed at patrolling the Aegean Sea, was underfunded and undermanned, with only 11 coastal patrol vessels, one ship, two helicopters, two aircraft, and a budget of €18 million.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A section of northeastern Croatia is believed to contain up to 60,000 unexploded land mines from the Croatian War of Independence in the 1990s.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Refugees were feared to be at risk of unknowingly detonating some of these minefields as they crossed the area.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] However, there were no reported cases of this happening in 2015 or 2016.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The number of people making the considerably more dangerous sea journey from northern Africa to Italy was comparatively low at around 150,000.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Most of the refugees and migrants taking this route came from African countries, especially Eritrea, Nigeria, and Somalia.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] At least 2,889 people died during the journey.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A few other routes were also used by some refugees, although they were comparatively low in number.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] One such route was entering Finland or Norway via Russia; on a few days Arctic border stations in these countries saw several hundred "irregular" border crossings per day.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Norway recorded around 6,000 refugees crossing its northern border in 2015.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Because it is illegal to drive from Russia to Norway without a permit, and crossing on foot is prohibited, some used a legal loophole and made the crossing by bicycle.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A year later in 2016, Norway built a short 200 m fence at the Storskog border crossing, although it was viewed as a mostly symbolic measure.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Some observers argued that the Russian government facilitated the influx in an attempt to warn European leaders against maintaining sanctions imposed after Russia's annexation of Crimea.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In January 2016, a Russian border guard admitted that the Russian Federal Security Service was enabling migrants to enter Finland.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Asylum seekers are usually required to be physically present in the EU country where they wish to request asylum.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] However, there are few formal ways to allow them to reach Europe for this purpose.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] For that reason, many asylum seekers paid smugglers for advice, logistical help and transportation through Europe, especially for sea crossings.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Human traffickers charged $1,000 to $1,500 (€901 – €1352) for the 25-minute boat ride from Bodrum, Turkey to Kos.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] An onward journey to Germany which would not necessarily involve smugglers was estimated to cost €3,000 – €4,000.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A journey to Britain was estimated to cost €10,000 – €12,000.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Airplane tickets directly from Turkey to Germany or Britain would have been far cheaper and safer, but the EU requires airlines flying into the Schengen Area to check that passengers have a visa or are exempted from carrying one (these rules are referred to as "carrier responsibility").
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] This prevented would-be migrants without a visa from being allowed on aircraft, boats, or trains entering the Schengen Area, and caused them to resort to smugglers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Humanitarian visas are generally not given to refugees who want to apply for asylum.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In September 2015, Europol estimated there were 30,000 suspected migrant smugglers operating in and around Europe.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] By the end of 2016, this number had increased to 55,000.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] 63 per cent of the smugglers were from Europe, 14 per cent from the Middle East, 13 per cent from Africa, nine per cent from Asia (excluding the Middle East) and one per cent from the Americas.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] On several occasions, unscrupulous smugglers caused the deaths of the people they were transporting, particularly by using poorly-maintained and overfilled boats and refusing to provide life jackets.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] At least 3771 refugees and migrants drowned in the Mediterranean Sea in 2015.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A single shipwreck near Lampedusa in April accounted for around 800 deaths.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Apart from drownings, the deadliest incident occurred on 27 August 2015, when 71 people were found dead in an unventilated food truck near Vienna.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Eleven of the smugglers responsible were later arrested and charged with murder and homicide in Hungary.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The charges and trial took place in Hungary as authorities determined that the deaths had occurred there.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The Mafia Capitale investigation revealed that the Italian Mafia profited from the migrant crisis and exploited refugees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Migrant and refugee arrivals in the EU, 2015–16.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Defined as monthly "irregular border crossings" into the EU.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The net number of refugees entering the EU is considerably lower because many migrants were double-counted as "illegally crossing an EU border": first when arriving in Greece, and again when entering the EU for the second time through Hungary or Croatia.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The first half of 2015 saw around 230,000 people enter the EU.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The most common points of entry were Italy and Greece.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] From there, arrivals either applied for asylum directly or attempted to travel to Northern and Western European countries, mostly by traveling through the Balkans and re-entering the EU through Hungary or Croatia.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Hungary was required by EU law to register them as asylum seekers and attempted to prevent them from traveling on to other EU countries.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] At the same time, Hungarian prime minister Viktor Orbán began using fear of immigration as a domestic political campaign issue and stated his opposition to accepting long-term refugees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] By August 2015, Hungary housed about 150,000 refugees in makeshift camps.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Many had little desire to stay in Hungary; due to the government's unwelcoming stance, squalid conditions in the camps, and their poor prospects of being allowed to stay.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Over the course of 2015 and 2016, almost everyone who had lodged an asylum claim in Hungary left the country.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] On 21 August 2015, the German Federal Office for Migration and Refugees was overwhelmed.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Due to their lack of capacity to process applications the German office suspended the Dublin Regulation for Syrians.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Interpreting this to mean that Germany would begin accepting larger numbers of refugees many immigrants attempted to reach Germany from Hungary and southeastern Europe.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] They were met with a warm reception from the German crowds.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] On 1 September, Hungarian government closed outbound rail traffic from Budapest's Keleti station, which many refugees were using to travel to Austria and Germany.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Within days, a massive buildup of people had formed at the station.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] On 4 September, several thousand set off to make the 150 km journey towards Austria on foot, at which point the Hungarian government relented and no longer tried to stop them.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In an effort to force the Austrian and German governments' hands, Hungary chartered buses to the Austrian border for both those walking and those who had stayed behind at the station.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Unwilling to resort to violence to keep them out, and faced with a potential humanitarian crisis if the huge numbers languished in Hungary indefinitely, Germany and Austria jointly announced on 4 September that they would allow the migrants to cross their borders and apply for asylum.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Across Germany, crowds formed at train stations to applaud and welcome the arrivals.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In the following three months, an estimated 550,000 people entered Germany to apply for asylum, around half the total for the entire year.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] This phrase quickly became a symbol of her government's refugee policy.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Although Austria also accepted some asylum seekers, for a time the country effectively became a distribution centre to Germany, slowing and regulating their transit into Germany and providing temporary housing, food and health care.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] On some days, Austria took in up to 10,000 Germany-bound migrants arriving from Slovenia and Hungary.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Germany's imposition of border controls had a domino effect on countries to Germany's southeast, as Austria and Slovakia successively enacted their own border controls.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Hungary closed its border with Serbia entirely with a fence that had been under construction for several months, forcing migrants to pass through Croatia and Slovenia instead.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Croatia tried to force them back into Hungary, which responded with military force.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Croatian and Hungarian leaders each blamed each other for the situation and engaged in a bitter back-and-forth about what to do about the tens of thousands of stranded people.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Three days later, Croatia likewise closed its border with Serbia to avoid becoming a transit country.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Slovenia kept its borders open, although it did limit the flow of people, resulting in occasionally violent clashes with police.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In October, Hungary also closed its border with Croatia, making Slovenia the only remaining way to reach Austria and Germany.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Croatia reopened its own border to Serbia and together with Slovenia began permitting migrants to pass through, providing buses and temporary accommodation en route.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Slovenia did impose a limit of 2,500 people per day, which initially stranded thousands of migrants in Croatia, Serbia and North Macedonia.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In November, Slovenia began erecting temporary fences along the border to direct the flow of people to formal border crossings.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Several countries, such as Hungary, Slovenia and Austria, authorized their armies to secure their borders or repel migrants; some passed legislation specifically to give armed forces more powers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] EU officials generally reacted with dismay at the border closures, warning that they undermined the mutual trust and freedom of movement that the bloc was founded on and risked returning to a pre-1990s arrangement of costly border controls and mistrust.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The European Commission warned EU members against steps that contravene EU treaties and urged members like Hungary to find other ways to cope with an influx of refugees and migrants.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] As winter set in, refugee numbers decreased, although they were still many times higher than in the previous year.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In January and February 2016, over 123,000 migrants landed in Greece, compared to about 4,600 in the same period of 2015.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Sweden took in over 160,000 refugees in 2015, more per capita than any other country in Europe (other than Turkey).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Well over half of these came to Sweden in October and November.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Most entered Sweden by traveling through Germany and then Denmark; few wanted to apply for asylum in Denmark because of its comparatively harsh conditions for asylum seekers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] There were occasionally scuffles as Danish police tried to register some of the arrivals, as they were technically required to do according to EU rules.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In early September, Denmark temporarily closed rail and road border crossings with Germany.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] After initial uncertainty surrounding the rules, Denmark allowed most of the people wishing to travel on to Sweden to do so.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In the five weeks following 6 September, approximately 28,800 refugees and migrants crossed the Danish borders, 3,500 of whom applied for asylum in Denmark; the rest continued to other Nordic countries.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In November 2015, Sweden reintroduced border controls at the Danish border, although this did not reduce the number of arrivals as they still had the right to apply for asylum.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Within hours of Swedish border control becoming effective, Denmark instituted border controls at the German border.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Some bypassed the border controls by taking a ferry to Trelleborg instead of the train to Hyllie, The border controls were never fully lifted before the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020, which saw renewed border closures throughout Europe.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In October 2015, the Slovenian government accused Croatian police of helping migrants bypass Slovene border controls and released a night time thermovision video allegedly documenting the event.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] After inspecting a refugee camp in Traiskirchen, Austria, in August 2015, Amnesty International noted inhabitants were receiving insufficient medical care and claimed Austria was "violating human rights".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In late November, Finnish reception centers were running out of space, which forced authorities to resort to refurbished shipping containers and tents to house new asylum seekers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Deputy prime minister Petteri Orpo announced that special repatriation centers would be established to house denied asylum seekers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] While he stressed that these camps would not be prisons, he stated that the inhabitants would be under strict surveillance.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Many migrants tried to enter the United Kingdom, resulting in camps of migrants around Calais where one of the Eurotunnel entrances is located.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In the summer of 2015, at least nine people died in attempts to reach Britain, including falling from trains, being hit by trains, or drowning in a canal at the Eurotunnel entrance.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In response, a UK-financed fence was built along the A-216 highway in Calais.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] At the camp near Calais, known as the *Jungle*, riots broke out when authorities began demolishing the illegally constructed campsite on 29 January 2015.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Amid the protests, which included hunger strikes, thousands of refugees living in the camp were relocated to France's "first international-standard refugee camp" at the La Liniere refugee camp in Grande-Synthe which replaced the previous Basroch refugee camp.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Germany has a quota system to distribute asylum seekers among all German states, but in September 2015 the federal states, responsible for accommodation, criticised the government in Berlin for not providing enough help to them.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In Germany, which took in by far the highest number of refugees, the federal government distributes refugees among the 16 states proportionally to their tax revenue and population; the states themselves are required to come up with housing solutions.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In 2015, this arrangement came under strain as many states ran out of dedicated accommodation for incoming refugees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Many resorted to temporarily housing refugees in tents or repurposed empty buildings.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The small village of Sumte (population 102), which contained a large unused warehouse, famously took in 750 refugees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Although media and some locals feared racial strife and a far-right political surge, the town remained peaceful and locals largely accepting.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] By 2020, most of the arrivals had moved on to bigger German cities for work or study; a small number settled in Sumte permanently.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Because the vast majority of refugees arriving in Europe in 2015 passed through Turkey, the country's cooperation was seen as central to efforts to stem the flow of people and prevent refugees from attempting to make dangerous sea crossings.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] There was also a recognition that it would be unfair to expect Turkey to shoulder the financial and logistical burden of hosting and integrating millions of refugees on its own.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In 2015, the European Commission began negotiating an agreement with Turkey to close its borders to Greece in exchange for money and diplomatic favours.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In March 2016, after months of tense negotiations during which Turkish president Recep Tayyip Erdoğan repeatedly threatened to open Turkey's borders and "flood" Europe with migrants to extract concessions, a deal was announced.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Turkey agreed to significantly increase border security at its shores and take back all future irregular entrants into Greece (and thereby the EU) from Turkey.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In return, the EU would pay Turkey 6 billion euros (around US$7 billion).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In addition, for every Syrian sent back from Greece, the EU would accept one registered Syrian refugee living in Turkey who had never tried to enter the EU illegally, up to a total of 72,000.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The EU also promised to institute visa-free travel to the Schengen area and to breathe new life into Turkey's EU accession talks.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The deal came into force on 20 March 2016.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] On 4 April, the first group of 200 people had been deported from Greece to Turkey under the provisions of the deal.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Turkey planned to deport most of them to their home countries.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The agreement resulted in a steep decline of migrant arrivals in Greece; in April, Greece recorded only 2,700 irregular border crossings, a 90 per cent decrease compared to the previous month.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] This was also the first time since June 2015 that more migrants arrived in Italy than in Greece.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The plan to send migrants back to Turkey was criticized by human right organisations and the United Nations, which warned that it could be illegal to send the migrants back to Turkey in exchange for financial and political rewards.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The UNHCR said it was not a party to the EU-Turkey deal and would not be involved in returns or detentions.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Like the UNHCR, four aid agencies (Médecins Sans Frontières, the International Rescue Committee, the Norwegian Refugee Council and Save the Children) said they would not help to implement the EU-Turkey deal because blanket expulsion of refugees contravened international law.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Amnesty International called the agreement "madness", and said 18 March 2016 was "a dark day for Refugee Convention, Europe and humanity".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Turkish prime minister Ahmet Davutoglu said that Turkey and EU had the same challenges, the same future, and the same destiny.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] President of the European Council Donald Tusk said that the migrants in Greece would not be sent back to dangerous areas.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Turkey's EU accession talks began in July 2016 and the first $3.3 billion was transferred to Turkey.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The talks were suspended in November 2016 after the Turkey's antidemocratic response to the 2016 Turkish coup attempt.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Erdoğan again threatened to flood Europe with migrants after the European Parliament voted to suspend EU membership talks in November 2016: "if you go any further, these border gates will be opened.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Neither me nor my people will be affected by these dry threats." Over the next few years, Turkish officials continued to threaten the EU with reneging on the deal and engineering a repeat of the 2015 refugee crisis in response to criticism of the Erdoğan government.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In one incident in March 2020, the Turkish government bused large numbers of Syrians living in Turkey to the Greek border and encouraged them to cross.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Greece repelled the arrivals with border guards.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] One effect of the closure of the "Balkan route" was to drive refugees to other routes, especially across the central and eastern Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] As a result, migrant deaths due to shipwrecks began increasing again.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] On 16 April, a large boat sank between Libya and Italy, with as many as 500 deaths.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In addition, countries that had seen comparatively few refugee arrivals began recording significant numbers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In 2017, for instance, there was a 60% significant jump in the number of migrants reaching Spain.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Similarly, Cyprus recorded an approximately 8-fold increase in the number of arrivals between 2016 and 2017.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In response to the increased numbers of people reaching Italian shores, Italy signed an agreement in early 2017 with the UN-recognized government of Libya, from where most migrants started their boat journeys to Italy.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In return for Libya making more efforts to prevent migrants from reaching Europe, Italy provided money and training for the Libyan coast guard and for migrant detention centres in northern Libya.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In August of that year, the Libyan Coast Guard began requiring NGO rescue vessels to stay at least 360 km (225 mi) from the Libyan coast unless they were given express permission to enter.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] As a result, NGOs MSF, Save the Children and Sea Eye suspended their operations after clashes with the Libyan Coast Guard after the latter asserted its sovereignty of its waters by firing warning shots.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Soon afterwards, refugee arrivals in Italy dropped significantly.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] At the same time, the lack of rescue vessels made the crossing much more dangerous; by September 2018, one in five migrants attempting to cross the Mediterranean Sea from Libya either drowned or disappeared.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In 2019, the deal was renewed for a further three years.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The response at the EU level was relatively uncoordinated, as some member states unilaterally closed their borders and others, like Germany and Sweden, maintained a relatively welcoming stance.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The sudden border closures often resulted in chaos, trapping large numbers of people in countries where they had no desire to stay.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The European Commission made some attempts to harmonize the different policies, such as the Common European Asylum System (CEAS).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In addition, the European Border and Coast Guard Agency focused on strengthening European border integrity in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Several policies, such as an "Emergency Trust Fund," were also developed to address problems in the home countries of asylum seekers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Non-governmental organizations often filled the vacuum official operations were insufficient.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Following the end of Italy's Mare Nostrum operation in 2014, NGOs began performing search and rescue operations.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Some Italian authorities feared that they encouraged people to use the dangerous passage facilitated by human traffickers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In July 2017, Italy drew up a code of conduct for NGO rescue vessels delivering migrants to Italian ports.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] These rules prohibited coordinating with human traffickers via flares or radio and required vessels to permit police presence on board.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] More controversially, they also forbade entering the territorial waters of Libya and transferring rescued people onto other vessels, which severely limited the number of people NGOs could save.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International criticised the code of conduct and some NGOs, including Doctors Without Borders, eventually suspended rescue operations.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In the years following its implementation, Mediterranean Sea crossings dropped considerably, although the degree to which this was caused by the NGO code is disputed.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A study conducted from 2014 to 2019 concluded that external factors like weather and the political stability of Libya contributed more to the ebbs and flows of migrants crossing the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Non-governmental search and rescue operations cannot entirely stop the loss of life at sea in the wake of large-scale migratory flows.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In September 2016, Greek volunteers of the "Hellenic Rescue Team" and human rights activist Efi Latsoudi were awarded the Nansen Refugee Award by the UNHCR "for their tireless volunteer work" in helping refugees arrive in Greece during the 2015 refugee crisis.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A 2016 study by Pew Research Center suggested widespread anxiety over the refugee crisis and immigration in general, particularly about effects on the labour market, crime, and difficulty integrating the newcomers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The study also revealed insecurities about weakening national identities when taking in people from other cultures.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Many Europeans also harbored more specific anxieties around Muslim immigration because Islam is incompatible with European values.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Some national leaders, notably in Slovakia and Hungary, exploited and at times encouraged this fear for electoral gain.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A study of ten European countries by Royal Institute of International Affairs found that an average of 55% would support stopping further immigration from Muslims, with support ranging from 40% (Spain) to 70% (Poland).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A study by the European Social Survey using more nuanced wording found that 25% were opposed to all Muslim immigration; a further 30% supported permitting only "some" Muslim immigration.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The public perception of the migrant crisis from the Hungarian point of view has been characterized as anti-immigration since 2015.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Muslim immigrants are perceived as a symbolic threat to the dominant—mostly Christian—Western culture, and (specifically in the Hungarian context) asylum seekers with a Christian background are more welcomed than those with a Muslim background.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A study released by the European Union Agency for Fundamental Rights found that almost 40% of first- and second-generation Muslims in Europe surveyed reported discrimination in their daily life.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] British Somali poet Warsan Shire's poem 'Home' became a prominent depiction of the refugee experience.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A video of Benedict Cumberbatch reciting the poem after a stage performance as part of an impassioned plea to help refugees went viral in September 2015.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A photo of the body of a 2-year-old Syrian boy named Alan Kurdi (after he drowned on 2 September 2015) became a symbol of the suffering of refugees trying to reach Europe.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Unlike many pictures of refugees often published in European media, in which "asylum-seekers are generally shown in groups of people, often on boats, rather than as single individuals", the picture was of a single, identifiable child victim and engendered a wave of compassion throughout Europe.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Multiple EU leaders addressed the photo and called for EU action to address the crisis.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Kurdi and his family were Syrian refugees, and 2-year-old Alan died alongside his brother and mother – only his father survived the journey, telling CNN "everything I was dreaming of is gone.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] I want to bury my children and sit beside them until I die." Kurdi's body was photographed by Turkish journalist Nilüfer Demir.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Pegida, a pan-European far-right political movement founded in 2014 on opposition to immigration from Muslim countries, experienced a resurgence during the refugee crisis, especially in eastern Germany.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The movement said that "Western civilisation could soon come to an end through Islam conquering Europe".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In the United Kingdom, members of the far-right anti-immigration group Britain First organised protest marches.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] An analysis by Hope not Hate, an anti-racist advocacy group, identified 24 different British groups attempting to whip up mistrust of Muslims and provoke a "cultural civil war", including the UK chapter of Pegida and the political party Liberty GB.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] White-nationalist conspiracy theories predicting a Muslim takeover of Europe gained wider prominence during and after the refugee crisis.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A theory known as Eurabia, which claims that globalist entities led by French and Arab powers are plotting to "islamise" and "arabise" Europe, was propagated widely in far-right circles.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Many groups also circulated a similar conspiracy theory called the "Great Replacement".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] More than 3,700 migrants died trying, usually by drowning.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Over 75% of asylum seekers arriving in Europe in 2015 were fleeing from Syria, Afghanistan or Iraq.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Other significant countries of origin were Kosovo, Albania, Pakistan and Eritrea.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Around half of asylum applications were made by young adults between 18 and 34 years of age; 96,000 refugees were unaccompanied minors.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Around three-quarters of applications were by men.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The gender imbalance among refugees reaching Europe has multiple related causes, most significantly the dangerous and expensive nature of the journey.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Men with families often travel to Europe alone with the intent of applying for family reunification once their asylum request is granted.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In addition, in many countries, such as Syria, men are at greater risk than women of being forcibly conscripted or killed.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Developing countries hosted the largest share of refugees (86 per cent by the end of 2014, the highest figure in more than two decades); the least developed countries alone provided asylum to 25 per cent of refugees worldwide.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] 52 per cent of asylum applications in the EU were granted in 2015; another 14 per cent were granted on appeal.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] The citizenships with the highest recognition rates at first instance were Syria (97.2 per cent), Eritrea (89.8 per cent), Iraq (85.7 per cent), Afghanistan (67 per cent), Iran (64.7 per cent), Somalia (63.1 per cent) and Sudan (56 per cent).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Asylum applications by citizens of some countries with high levels of violence, like Nigeria and Pakistan, nevertheless had low success rates.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Some people applying for asylum were perceived to be economic migrants using the asylum process to move to Europe to find work, rather than fleeing war or persecution.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Economic migrants are not eligible for asylum, although the distinction between economic migrants and refugees is not always clear since some people fleeing war are also fleeing poverty.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] It is difficult to say what proportion of the 2015 arrivals to Europe were "economic migrants." Some analysts use refugee recognition rates as a metric, although this is also difficult since these vary widely between EU countries.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] People from the Western Balkans — most of whom were Romanis, a marginalized ethnic group — were often perceived to be economic migrants.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Parts of West Africa and Pakistan also had low recognition rates.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] However, these nationalities made up a relatively small percentage of 2015 arrivals.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In 2015, 14% of all first-time asylum requests filed in the EU were by people from the Western Balkans; in 2016 the figure was 5%.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Syrians, Afghans and Iraqis, whose asylum recognition rates ranged between 60% and 100% in Germany (which accepted by far the largest number of refugees in 2015) together filed around half of all asylum requests in both years.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Some argue that migrants have been seeking to settle preferentially in national destinations that offer more generous social welfare benefits and host more established Middle Eastern and African immigrant communities.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] Others argue that migrants are attracted to more tolerant societies with stronger economies, and that the chief motivation for leaving Turkey is that they are not permitted to leave camps or work.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] A large number of refugees in Turkey have been faced with difficult living circumstances; thus, many refugees arriving in southern Europe continue their journey in attempts to reach northern European countries such as Germany, which are observed as having more prominent outcomes of security.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p01] In contrast to Germany, France's popularity eroded in 2015 among migrants seeking asylum after being historically considered a popular final destination for the EU migrants.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The Russian Federation released an official statement on 2 September 2015 reporting that the United Nations Security Council was working on a draft resolution to address the European migrant crisis, likely by permitting the inspection of suspected migrant ships.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The International Organization for Migration claimed that deaths at sea increased ninefold after the end of Operation Mare Nostrum.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Amnesty International condemned European governments for "negligence towards the humanitarian crisis in the Mediterranean" which they say led to an increase in deaths at sea.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In April 2015, Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch criticised the funding of search and rescue operations.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Amnesty International said that the EU was "turning its back on its responsibilities and clearly threatening thousands of lives".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Australian prime minister Tony Abbott said the tragedies were "worsened by Europe's refusal to learn from its own mistakes and from the efforts of others who have handled similar problems.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] President Barack Obama praised Germany for taking a leading role in accepting refugees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] During his April 2016 visit to Germany, he praised German Chancellor Angela Merkel for being on "the right side of history" with her open-border immigration policy.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In March 2016, NATO General Philip Breedlove stated, "Together, Russia and the Assad regime are deliberately weaponizing migration in an attempt to overwhelm European structures and break European resolve. ..
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] On 18 June 2016, United Nations chief Ban Ki-moon also called for international support and praised Greece for showing "remarkable solidarity and compassion" towards refugees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The lack of action by UNESCO in this area was the subject of controversy.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Some scholars, like António Silva, blamed UNESCO for not denouncing racism against war refugees in Europe with the same vigor as the vandalism against ancient monuments perpetrated by fundamentalists in the Middle East.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Following the European Union's measures to prevent asylum seekers from reaching its borders, monthly arrivals dropped to around 10,000–20,000 in spring 2016.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Arrival numbers fell in each of the following years, dropping to 95,000 by 2020.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Turkish president Recep Tayyip Erdoğan continued to occasionally threaten to renege on Turkey's agreement to prevent migrants and refugees from reaching Europe, often demanding more cash or retaliating for European criticism of Turkey's human rights record.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The refugee crisis polarized European society.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In Western Europe, large majorities supported accepting refugees fleeing violence and war, while Eastern Europeans were generally more ambivalent.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] At the same time, however, large majorities also disapproved of the EU's handling of the refugee wave.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] As southeastern European countries began seeing large numbers of refugees and migrants began moving through them, political leaders began to capitalize on the uncertainty felt by locals.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The Hungarian prime minister, Viktor Orbán, in particular began to campaign on fear of immigration, calling refugees "Muslim invaders", conflating migrants with terrorism, and stating that they were part of a "left-wing conspiracy" to gain new voters.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In October, Czech President Miloš Zeman used similar rhetoric to campaign on opposition to refugees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The refugee crisis was also a major issue in Poland's 2015 parliamentary elections, with then-opposition leader Jarosław Kaczyński in particular stoking fear of immigrants and claiming the EU was planning to flood Poland with Muslims.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Under incumbent prime minister Ewa Kopacz, Poland had agreed to accept 2,000 refugees as part of the European Union's plan to distribute a fraction of that year's arrivals, while at the same time opposing the settlement of "economic migrants".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] After Kaczyński's Law and Justice party won the elections, Poland rescinded its willingness to cooperate with the European Commission.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Nigel Farage, leader of the British United Kingdom Independence Party, said that Islamists could exploit the situation and enter Europe in large numbers.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In western European countries, although support for refugees was generally high, far-right leaders fiercely opposed allowing the newly arrived refugees to stay.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Matteo Salvini, leader of Italy's League, described the migration as a "planned invasion" which must be stopped.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Geert Wilders, leader of the Dutch Party for Freedom, called the influx of people an "Islamic invasion" and spoke of "masses of young men in their twenties with beards singing *Allahu Akbar* across Europe".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Marine Le Pen, leader of the French far-right National Front, was criticized by German media for implying that Germany was looking to undercut minimum wage laws and hire "slaves".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Germany's acceptance of over 1 million asylum seekers was controversial both within Angela Merkel's centre-right Christian Democratic Union party and among the general public.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Pegida, an anti-immigration protest movement that had flourished briefly in late 2014, experienced a resurgence at the end of summer 2015.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Many members of parliament for the CDU voiced dissatisfaction with Merkel.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Horst Seehofer, then premier of Bavaria, became a prominent critic within the CDU of Merkel's refugee policy and alleged that as many as 30 per cent of Germany's asylum seekers claiming to be from Syria were in fact from other countries.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Yasmin Fahimi, secretary-general of the centre-left Social Democratic Party (SPD), the junior partner of the ruling coalition, praised Merkel's policy allowing migrants in Hungary to enter Germany as "a strong signal of humanity to show that Europe's values are valid also in difficult times".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In the 2017 German federal election, the right-wing populist Alternative for Germany (AfD) gained 12% of the vote, which was attributed in part to anxieties around immigration.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The Hungarian government under Fidesz held a referendum in 2016, where the overwhelming majority (98.4%) rejected the EU's mandatory migrant quotas, although the result was not considered valid because turnout fell short of the required 50% threshold, due to the opposition boycotting the referendum.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The 2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum took place on 23 June 2016, around nine months after peak of the refugee crisis.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The UK was never a member of the Schengen Area and so experienced very few direct effects of the influx of migrants.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Nevertheless, Leave.EU, one of the two main groups campaigning in favour of Brexit, made the refugee crisis its defining issue (the other main pro-Leave group, Vote Leave, primarily focused on economic arguments).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The campaign portrayed the European Union as inept and unable to control its borders, and conflated the refugee crisis with unease over Turkey's application to join the EU (although very few of the 2015 refugees were from Turkey).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The Brexit vote resulted in a narrow decision to leave the EU (51.9% to 48.1%).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] According to exit polls, one third of Leave voters believed leaving the EU would allow Britain to better control immigration and its own borders.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] As of 2024, 64% of the migrants who had arrived in Germany in 2015 were employed, compared with 70% of the general population, although they earn around 30% less than the full-time median salary in the country.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] There is also a strong gender split, with 74% of men employed but only 35% of women.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In 2022, around 95% of migrants who had arrived in Germany in 2015 had taken a German language course.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] People whose asylum applications are rejected are generally required to return to their home countries.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Some do so voluntarily; others are deported.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] However, deportation is often difficult in practice; a common reason is lacking travel documents or the person's country of origin refusing to accept returnees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The annual rate of return has generally averaged around one-third.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In some countries that took in large numbers of asylum seekers, this has resulted in tens of thousands of people not having legal residency rights, raising worries of institutionalised poverty and the creation of parallel societies.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The years following the 2015 refugee crisis saw some European countries enact legislation to speed up deportations.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The EU began threatening to withhold development aid from or impose visa restrictions on countries refusing to take in their own citizens.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] For a variety of reasons, some rejected asylum seekers also ended up being permitted to stay.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Some countries, such as Germany and Sweden, allow rejected asylum seekers to apply for certain other visas (e.g., to pursue vocational training if they have secured an apprenticeship).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Around November 2015, some European countries restricted family reunions for refugees, and started campaigns to dissuade people worldwide to migrate to Europe.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] EU leaders also quietly encouraged Balkan governments to only allow nationals from the most war-torn countries (Syria, Afghanistan and Iraq) to pass into the EU.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In 2016 Sweden began issuing three-year residence permits to recognized refugees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Refugees had previously received permanent residency automatically.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In January 2016, Denmark passed a law permitting police to confiscate valuables like jewelry and cash from refugees.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] As of early 2019, the police had only enforced the cash-seizing provision.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Refugees, who have often fled violence their home countries and experienced further violence during their journey, have high rates of post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD).
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In 2016 in Sweden, 30% of Syrian refugees were estimated to suffer from PTSD, depression, and anxiety.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In 2020, a study of physically healthy young refugees in Germany identified 40% as having risk factors for PTSD.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Long asylum claim processing times, during which refugees cannot work or travel and contemplate being sent back to their home country, often compound poor mental health.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Although asylum applications are in principle supposed to be processed within six months on average, many countries that took in significantly more refugees than in previous years took considerably longer – in many cases over year and sometimes up to two.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In Germany, refugees do not have access to non-acute medical care, including therapy mental health treatments, until they have lived in the country for at least 15 months.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Language barriers also often make therapy particularly difficult.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The Cardiff School of Journalism, in a report on behalf of UNHCR, analysed several thousand media reports on the refugee crisis in Spain, Italy, United Kingdom, Germany and Sweden.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] A similar split was apparent in the reasons for people fleeing their home countries: right-wing newspapers were more likely to mention economic reasons than left-of-centre ones.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The study also found significant differences between countries, noting that right-wing media in the United Kingdom had conducted a "uniquely aggressive campaign" against refugees and migrants in 2015.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Threats to welfare systems and cultural threats were most prevalent in Italy, Spain, and Britain while humanitarian themes were more frequent in Italian coverage.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] More subtle differences in were found in the terminology used: German and Swedish media overwhelmingly used the terms *refugee* or *asylum seeker* while Italy and UK were more likely to use the term *migrant*.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In Spain, the dominant term was *immigrant*.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Overall the Swedish press was most positive towards the arrivals.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Journalist Will Hutton for the British newspaper *The Guardian* praised Angela Merkel's leadership during the refugee crisis: "Angela Merkel's humane stance on migration is a lesson to us all...
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] The German leader has stood up to be counted.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] She wants to keep Germany and Europe open, to welcome legitimate asylum seekers in common humanity, while doing her very best to stop abuse and keep the movement to manageable proportions.
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] Which demands a European-wide response (...)".
[src:ancient-rome/2015-european-migrant-crisis-p02] In March 2016, the UK's *Daily Telegraph* said that Merkel's 2015 decisions concerning migration represented an "open door policy", which it said was "encouraging migration into Europe that her own country is unwilling to absorb" and as damaging the EU, "perhaps terminally".
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Initially influenced by Toulouse-Lautrec, Gauguin, and other late-19th-century innovators, Pablo Picasso made his first cubist paintings based on Cézanne's idea that all depiction of nature can be reduced to three solids: cube, sphere, and cone.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With the painting *Les Demoiselles d'Avignon* (1907; see gallery) Picasso created a new and radical picture depicting a raw and primitive brothel scene with five prostitutes, violently painted women, reminiscent of African tribal masks and his own new proto-Cubist inventions.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism, exemplified by *Violin and Candlestick, Paris*, was jointly developed by Pablo Picasso and Georges Braque from about 1908 through 1912.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Analytic cubism was followed by Synthetic cubism, characterized by the introduction of different textures, surfaces, collage elements, papier collé and a large variety of merged subject matter.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the years between 1910 and the end of World War I and after the heyday of cubism, several movements emerged in Paris.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Giorgio de Chirico moved to Paris in July 1911, where he joined his brother Andrea (the poet and painter known as Alberto Savinio).
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Through his brother he met Pierre Laprade, a member of the jury at the Salon d'Automne, where he exhibited three of his dreamlike works: *Enigma of the Oracle*, *Enigma of an Afternoon* and *Self-Portrait*.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During 1913 he exhibited his work at the Salon des Indépendants and Salon d’Automne, where his work was noticed by Pablo Picasso, Guillaume Apollinaire, and others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His compelling and mysterious paintings are considered instrumental to the early beginnings of Surrealism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Song of Love* (1914) is one of the most famous works by de Chirico and is an early example of the surrealist style, though it was painted ten years before the movement was "founded" by André Breton in 1924.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Modern painting influenced all the visual arts, from Modernist architecture and design, to avant-garde film, theatre and modern dance, and became an experimental laboratory for the expression of visual experience, from photography and concrete poetry to advertising art and fashion.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Van Gogh's paintings exerted great influence upon 20th-century Expressionism, as can be seen in the work of the Fauves, Die Brücke (a group led by German painter Ernst Kirchner), and the Expressionism of Edvard Munch, Egon Schiele, Marc Chagall, Amedeo Modigliani, Chaïm Soutine, and others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Wassily Kandinsky, a Russian painter, printmaker and art theorist, is generally considered the first important painter of modern abstract art.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As an early modernist, in search of new modes of visual expression, and spiritual expression, he theorized—as did contemporary occultists and theosophists—that pure visual abstraction had corollary vibrations with sound and music.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] They posited that pure abstraction could express pure spirituality.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His earliest abstractions were generally titled (as the example in the above gallery) *Composition VII*, making connection to the work of the composers of music.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kandinsky included many of his theories about abstract art in his book *Concerning the Spiritual in Art*.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Piet Mondrian's art was also related to his spiritual and philosophical studies.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1908 he became interested in the theosophical movement launched by Helena Petrovna Blavatsky in the late 19th century.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Blavatsky believed that it was possible to attain a knowledge of nature more profound than that provided by empirical means, and much of Mondrian's work for the rest of his life was inspired by his search for that spiritual knowledge.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other major pioneers of early abstraction include Swedish painter Hilma af Klint, Russian painter Kazimir Malevich, and Swiss painter Paul Klee.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Robert Delaunay was a French artist who is associated with Orphism, (reminiscent of a link between pure abstraction and cubism).
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His later works were more abstract, reminiscent of Paul Klee.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His key contributions to abstract painting refer to his bold use of color, and a clear love of experimentation of both depth and tone.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] At the invitation of Kandinsky, Delaunay and his wife the artist Sonia Delaunay, joined The Blue Rider (Der Blaue Reiter), a Munich-based group of abstract artists, in 1911, and his art took a turn to the abstract.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Still other important pioneers of abstract painting include Czech painter, František Kupka as well as American artists Stanton Macdonald-Wright and Morgan Russell who, in 1912, founded Synchromism, an art movement that closely resembles Orphism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Les Fauves (French for *The Wild Beasts*) were early-20th-century painters, experimenting with freedom of expression through color.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name was given, humorously and not as a compliment, to the group by art critic Louis Vauxcelles.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism was a short-lived and loose grouping of artists whose works emphasized painterly qualities and the imaginative use of deep color over the representational values.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvists made the subject of the painting easy to read and exaggerated perspectives.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The leaders of the movement were Henri Matisse and André Derain—friendly rivals of a sort, each with his own followers.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ultimately Matisse became the *yang* to Picasso's *yin* in the 20th century.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvist painters included Albert Marquet, Charles Camoin, Maurice de Vlaminck, Raoul Dufy, Othon Friesz, the Dutch painter Kees van Dongen, and Picasso's partner in Cubism, Georges Braque amongst others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Fauvism, as a movement, had no concrete theories, and was short lived, beginning in 1905 and ending in 1907.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse was seen as the leader of the movement, due to his seniority in age and prior self-establishment in the academic art world.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Matisse, *The Green Line* (above), caused a sensation in Paris when it was first exhibited.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He said he wanted to create art to delight; art as a decoration was his purpose and it can be said that his use of bright colors tries to maintain serenity of composition.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1906 at the suggestion of his dealer Ambroise Vollard, André Derain went to London and produced a series of paintings like *Charing Cross Bridge, London* (above) in the Fauvist style, paraphrasing the famous series by the Impressionist painter Claude Monet.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] By 1907 Fauvism no longer was a shocking new movement, soon it was replaced by Cubism on the critics radar screen as the latest new development in Contemporary Art of the time.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter was a German movement lasting from 1911 to 1914, fundamental to Expressionism, along with Die Brücke, a group of German expressionist artists formed in Dresden in 1905.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Founding members of Die Brücke were Fritz Bleyl, Erich Heckel, Ernst Ludwig Kirchner and Karl Schmidt-Rottluff.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Later members included Max Pechstein, Otto Mueller and others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This was a seminal group, which in due course had a major impact on the evolution of modern art in the 20th century and created the style of Expressionism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Der Blaue Reiter lacked a central artistic manifesto, but was centered around Kandinsky and Marc.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists Gabriele Münter and Paul Klee were also involved.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The name of the movement comes from a painting by Kandinsky created in 1903.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is also claimed that the name could have derived from Marc's enthusiasm for horses and Kandinsky's love of the colour blue.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] For Kandinsky, *blue* is the colour of spirituality: the darker the blue, the more it awakens human desire for the eternal.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Marcel Duchamp came to international prominence in the wake of the New York City Armory Show in 1913 where his *Nude Descending a Staircase* became the *cause célèbre*.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He subsequently created *The Bride Stripped Bare by Her Bachelors, Even, Large Glass*.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Large Glass* pushed the art of painting to radical new limits being part painting, part collage, part construction.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp (who was soon to renounce artmaking for chess) became closely associated with the Dada movement that began in neutral Zürich, Switzerland, during World War I and peaked from 1916 to 1920.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The movement primarily involved visual arts, literature (poetry, art manifestoes, art theory), theatre, and graphic design, and concentrated its anti war politic through a rejection of the prevailing standards in art through anti-art cultural works.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Francis Picabia, Man Ray, Kurt Schwitters, Tristan Tzara, Hans Richter, Jean Arp, Sophie Taeuber-Arp, along with Duchamp and many others are associated with the Dadaist movement.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Duchamp and several Dadaists are also associated with Surrealism, the movement that dominated European painting in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1924 André Breton published the *Surrealist Manifesto.* The Surrealist movement in painting became synonymous with the avant-garde and which featured artists whose works varied from the abstract to the super-realist.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] With works on paper like *Machine Turn Quickly* (above) Francis Picabia continued his involvement in the Dada movement through 1919 in Zürich and Paris, before breaking away from it after developing an interest in Surrealist art.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Yves Tanguy, René Magritte and Salvador Dalí are particularly known for their realistic depictions of dream imagery and fantastic manifestations of the imagination.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Joan Miró's *The Tilled Field* of 1923–1924 verges on abstraction, this early painting of a complex of objects and figures, and arrangements of sexually active characters; was Miró's first Surrealist masterpiece.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The more abstract Joan Miró, Jean Arp, André Masson, and Max Ernst were very influential, especially in the United States during the 1940s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 1930s, Surrealism continued to become more visible to the public at large.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] A Surrealist group developed in Britain and, according to Breton, their 1936 London International Surrealist Exhibition was a high-water mark of the period and became the model for international exhibitions.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Surrealist groups in Japan, and especially in Latin America, the Caribbean and in Mexico produced innovative and original works.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí and Magritte created some of the most widely recognized images of the movement.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1928/1929 painting *This Is Not A Pipe* by Magritte is the subject of a Michel Foucault 1973 book, *This is not a Pipe* (English edition, 1991), that discusses the painting and its paradox.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Dalí joined the group in 1929, and participated in the rapid establishment of the visual style between 1930 and 1935.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Evocations of time and its compelling mystery and absurdity.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Max Ernst studied philosophy and psychology in Bonn and was interested in the alternative realities experienced by the insane.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] His paintings, such as *Murdering Airplane* (1920), may have been inspired by the psychoanalyst Sigmund Freud's study of the delusions of a paranoiac, Daniel Paul Schreber.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Freud identified Schreber's fantasy of becoming a woman as a *castration complex*.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The central image of two pairs of legs refers to Schreber's hermaphroditic desires.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Ernst's inscription on the back of the painting reads: *The picture is curious because of its symmetry.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s André Masson's work was enormously influential in helping the young artist Joan Miró find his roots in the new Surrealist painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Miró acknowledged in letters to his dealer Pierre Matisse the importance of Masson as an example to him in his early years in Paris.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Long after personal, political and professional tensions have fragmented the Surrealist group into thin air and ether, Magritte, Miró, Dalí and the other Surrealists continue to define a visual program in the arts.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other prominent surrealist artists include Giorgio de Chirico, Méret Oppenheim, Toyen, Grégoire Michonze, Roberto Matta, Kay Sage, Leonora Carrington, Dorothea Tanning, and Leonor Fini among others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1920s and the 1930s and the Great Depression, the European art scene was characterized by Surrealism, late Cubism, the Bauhaus, De Stijl, Dada, Neue Sachlichkeit, and Expressionism; and was occupied by masterful modernist color painters like Henri Matisse and Pierre Bonnard.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Scene painting and the Social Realism and Regionalism movements that contained both political and social commentary dominated the art world in the USA.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, Grant Wood, George Tooker, John Steuart Curry, Reginald Marsh, and others became prominent.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo's Symbolist works also relate strongly to Surrealism and to the Magic Realism movement in literature.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The psychological drama in many of Kahlo's self-portraits (above) underscore the vitality and relevance of her paintings to artists in the 21st century.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Germany Neue Sachlichkeit ("New Objectivity") emerged as Max Beckmann, Otto Dix, George Grosz and others associated with the Berlin Secession politicized their paintings.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The work of these artists grew out of expressionism, and was a response to the political tensions of the Weimar Republic, and was often sharply satirical.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Diego Rivera is perhaps best known by the public for his 1933 mural, *Man at the Crossroads*, in the lobby of the RCA Building at Rockefeller Center.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] When his patron Nelson Rockefeller discovered that the mural included a portrait of Lenin and other communist imagery, he fired Rivera, and the unfinished work was eventually destroyed by Rockefeller's staff.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The film *Cradle Will Rock* includes a dramatization of the controversy.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Frida Kahlo (Rivera's wife's) works are often characterized by their stark portrayals of pain.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Of her 143 paintings 55 are self-portraits, which frequently incorporate symbolic portrayals of her physical and psychological wounds.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Kahlo was deeply influenced by indigenous Mexican culture, which is apparent in her paintings' bright colors and dramatic symbolism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Christian and Jewish themes are often depicted in her work as well; she combined elements of the classic religious Mexican tradition—which were often bloody and violent—with surrealist renderings.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] While her paintings are not overtly Christian—she was an avowed communist—they certainly contain elements of the macabre Mexican Christian style of religious paintings.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s radical leftist politics characterized many of the artists connected to Surrealism, including Pablo Picasso.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] On 26 April 1937, during the Spanish Civil War, the Basque town of Gernika was the scene of the "Bombing of Gernika" by the Condor Legion of Nazi Germany's Luftwaffe.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The Germans were attacking to support the efforts of Francisco Franco to overthrow the Basque Government and the Spanish Republican government.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The town was devastated, though the Biscayan assembly and the Oak of Gernika survived.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted his mural sized *Guernica* to commemorate the horrors of the bombing.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In its final form, *Guernica* is an immense black and white, 3.5 metre (11 ft) tall and 7.8 metre (23 ft) wide mural painted in oil.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The mural presents a scene of death, violence, brutality, suffering, and helplessness without portraying their immediate causes.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The choice to paint in black and white contrasts with the intensity of the scene depicted and invokes the immediacy of a newspaper photograph.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Picasso painted the mural sized painting called *Guernica* in protest of the bombing.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting was first exhibited in Paris in 1937, then Scandinavia, then London in 1938 and finally in 1939 at Picasso's request the painting was sent to the United States in an extended loan (for safekeeping) at MoMA.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The painting went on a tour of museums throughout the U.S. until its final return to the Museum of Modern Art in New York City where it was exhibited for nearly thirty years.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Finally in accord with Picasso's wish to give the painting to the people of Spain as a gift, it was sent to Spain in 1981.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the Great Depression of the 1930s, through the years of World War II American art was characterized by Social Realism and American Scene Painting (as seen above) in the work of Grant Wood, Edward Hopper, Ben Shahn, Thomas Hart Benton, and several others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] *Nighthawks* (1942) is a painting by Edward Hopper that portrays people sitting in a downtown diner late at night.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is not only Hopper's most famous painting, but one of the most recognizable in American art.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is currently in the collection of the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The scene was inspired by a diner (since demolished) in Greenwich Village, Hopper's home neighborhood in Manhattan.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Hopper began painting it immediately after the attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After this event there was a large feeling of gloominess over the country, a feeling that is portrayed in the painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The urban street is empty outside the diner, and inside none of the three patrons is apparently looking or talking to the others but instead is lost in their own thoughts.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This portrayal of modern urban life as empty or lonely is a common theme throughout Hopper's work.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The 1940s in New York City heralded the triumph of American abstract expressionism, a modernist movement that combined lessons learned from Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Surrealism, Joan Miró, Cubism, Fauvism, and early Modernism via great teachers in America like Hans Hofmann and John D.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American artists benefited from the presence of Piet Mondrian, Fernand Léger, Max Ernst and the André Breton group, Pierre Matisse's gallery, and Peggy Guggenheim's The Art of This Century Gallery, as well as other factors.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Abstract Expressionism got its name in 1946 from the art critic Robert Coates.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It is seen as combining the emotional intensity and self-denial of the German Expressionists with the anti-figurative aesthetic of the European abstract schools such as Futurism, the Bauhaus and Synthetic Cubism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract Expressionism, Action painting, and Color Field painting are synonymous with the New York School.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Technically Surrealism was an important predecessor for Abstract expressionism with its emphasis on spontaneous, automatic or subconscious creation.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Jackson Pollock's dripping paint onto a canvas laid on the floor is a technique that has its roots in the work of André Masson.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Another important early manifestation of what came to be abstract expressionism is the work of American Northwest artist Mark Tobey, especially his "white writing" canvases, which, though generally not large in scale, anticipate the "all over" look of Pollock's drip paintings.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Additionally, abstract expressionism has an image of being rebellious, anarchic, highly idiosyncratic and, some feel, rather nihilistic.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In practice, the term is applied to any number of artists working (mostly) in New York who had quite different styles, and even applied to work which is not especially abstract nor expressionist.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Pollock's energetic "action paintings", with their "busy" feel, are different both technically and aesthetically, to the violent and grotesque *Women* series of Willem de Kooning.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As seen above in the gallery *Woman V* is one of a series of six paintings made by de Kooning between 1950 and 1953 that depict a three-quarter-length female figure.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He began the first of these paintings, *Woman I* collection: The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, in June 1950, repeatedly changing and painting out the image until January or February 1952, when the painting was abandoned unfinished.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The art historian Meyer Schapiro saw the painting in de Kooning's studio soon afterwards and encouraged the artist to persist.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Kooning's response was to begin three other paintings on the same theme; *Woman II*, The Museum of Modern Art, New York City, *Woman III*, Tehran Museum of Contemporary Art, *Woman IV*, Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the summer of 1952, spent at East Hampton, de Kooning further explored the theme through drawings and pastels.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] He may have finished work on *Woman I* by the end of June, or possibly as late as November 1952, and probably the other three women pictures were concluded at much the same time.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The *Woman series* are decidedly figurative paintings.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Both Hans Hofmann and Robert Motherwell (gallery) can be comfortably described as practitioners of action painting and Color field painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism has many stylistic similarities to the Russian artists of the early twentieth century such as Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although it is true that spontaneity or of the impression of spontaneity characterized many of the abstract expressionists works, most of these paintings involved careful planning, especially since their large size demanded it.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] An exception might be the drip paintings of Pollock.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Why this style gained mainstream acceptance in the 1950s is a matter of debate.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] American Social realism had been the mainstream in the 1930s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It had been influenced not only by the Great Depression but also by the Social Realists of Mexico such as David Alfaro Siqueiros and Diego Rivera.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The political climate after World War II did not long tolerate the social protests of those painters.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionism arose during World War II and began to be showcased during the early 1940s at galleries in New York like The Art of This Century Gallery.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The late 1940s through the mid-1950s ushered in the McCarthy era.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It was after World War II and a time of political conservatism and extreme artistic censorship in the United States.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Some people have conjectured that since the subject matter was often totally abstract, Abstract expressionism became a safe strategy for artists to pursue this style.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract art could be seen as apolitical.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Or if the art was political, the message was largely for the insiders.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] However those theorists are in the minority.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As the first truly original school of painting in America, Abstract expressionism demonstrated the vitality and creativity of the country in the post-war years, as well as its ability (or need) to develop an aesthetic sense that was not constrained by the European standards of beauty.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Although Abstract expressionism spread quickly throughout the United States, the major centers of this style were New York City and California, especially in the New York School, and the San Francisco Bay area.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Abstract expressionist paintings share certain characteristics, including the use of large canvases, an "all-over" approach, in which the whole canvas is treated with equal importance (as opposed to the center being of more interest than the edges).
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The canvas as the *arena* became a credo of Action painting, while the *integrity of the picture plane* became a credo of the Color Field painters.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1950s, Color Field painting initially referred to a particular type of abstract expressionism, especially the work of Mark Rothko, Clyfford Still, Barnett Newman, Robert Motherwell and Adolph Gottlieb.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It essentially involved abstract paintings with large, flat expanses of color that expressed the sensual, and visual feelings and properties of large areas of nuanced surface.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Art critic Clement Greenberg perceived Color Field painting as related to but different from Action painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The overall expanse and gestalt of the work of the early color field painters speaks of an almost religious experience, awestruck in the face of an expanding universe of sensuality, color and surface.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Artists like Clyfford Still, Mark Rothko, Hans Hofmann, Morris Louis, Jules Olitski, Kenneth Noland, Helen Frankenthaler, Larry Zox, and others often used greatly reduced references to nature, and they painted with a highly articulated and psychological use of color.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In general these artists eliminated recognizable imagery.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In *Mountains and Sea,* from 1952, a seminal work of Colorfield painting by Helen Frankenthaler the artist used the stain technique for the first time.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Europe there was the continuation of Surrealism, Cubism, Dada and the works of Matisse.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Also in Europe, Tachisme (the European equivalent to Abstract expressionism) and Informalism took hold of the newest generation.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Serge Poliakoff, Nicolas de Staël, Georges Mathieu, Vieira da Silva, Jean Dubuffet, Yves Klein and Pierre Soulages among others are considered important figures in post-war European painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Eventually abstract painting in America evolved into movements such as Neo-Dada, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, Neo-expressionism and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] As a response to the tendency toward abstraction imagery emerged through various new movements, notably Pop art.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the 1930s through the 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Abstract Expressionism, Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, and Lyrical abstraction.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Other artists reacted as a response to the tendency toward abstraction allowing imagery to continue through various new contexts like the Bay Area Figurative Movement in the 1950s and new forms of expressionism from the 1940s through the 1960s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In Italy during this time, Giorgio Morandi was the foremost still life painter, exploring a wide variety of approaches to depicting everyday bottles and kitchen implements.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Throughout the 20th century many painters practiced Realism and used expressive imagery; practicing landscape and figurative painting with contemporary subjects and solid technique, and unique expressivity like Milton Avery, John D.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham, Fairfield Porter, Edward Hopper, Andrew Wyeth, Balthus, Francis Bacon, Frank Auerbach, Lucian Freud, Leon Kossoff, Philip Pearlstein, Willem de Kooning, Arshile Gorky, Grace Hartigan, Robert De Niro, Sr., Elaine de Kooning and others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with Henri Matisse, Pablo Picasso, Pierre Bonnard, Georges Braque, and other 20th-century masters.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] The figurative work of Francis Bacon, Frida Kahlo, Edward Hopper, Lucian Freud Andrew Wyeth and others served as a kind of alternative to abstract expressionism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] One of the most well-known images in 20th-century American art is Wyeth's painting, *Christina's World*, currently in the collection of the Museum of Modern Art in New York City.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] It depicts a woman lying on the ground in a treeless, mostly tawny field, looking up at and crawling towards a gray house on the horizon; a barn and various other small outbuildings are adjacent to the house.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] This tempera work, done in a realist style, is nearly always on display at the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Arshile Gorky's portrait of what may be his friend Willem de Kooning (left) is an example of the evolution of Abstract Expressionism from the context of figure painting, cubism and surrealism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Along with his friends de Kooning and John D.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Graham Gorky created bio-morphically shaped and abstracted figurative compositions that by the 1940s evolved into totally abstract paintings.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Gorky's work seems to be a careful analysis of memory, emotion and shape, using line and color to express feeling and nature.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] After World War II the term School of Paris often referred to Tachisme, the European equivalent of American Abstract expressionism and those artists are also related to Cobra.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] In 1952 Michel Tapié authored the book *Un Autre art* which gave name and voice to Informalism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Important proponents being Jean Dubuffet, Pierre Soulages, Nicolas de Staël, Hans Hartung, Serge Poliakoff, and Georges Mathieu, among several others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] During the early 1950s Dubuffet (who was always a figurative artist), and de Staël, abandoned abstraction, and returned to imagery via figuration and landscape.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] De Staël 's work was quickly recognised within the post-war art world, and he became one of the most influential artists of the 1950s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Much of de Staël 's late work – in particular his thinned, and diluted oil on canvas abstract landscapes of the mid-1950s predicts Color Field painting and Lyrical Abstraction of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p01] Nicolas de Staël's bold and intensely vivid color in his last paintings predict the direction of much of contemporary painting that came after him including Pop art of the 1960s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art in America was to a large degree initially inspired by the works of Jasper Johns, Larry Rivers, and Robert Rauschenberg.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although the paintings of Gerald Murphy, Stuart Davis and Charles Demuth during the 1920s and 1930s set the table for Pop art in America.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In New York City during the mid-1950s Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns created works of art that at first seemed to be continuations of Abstract expressionist painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Actually their works and the work of Larry Rivers, were radical departures from abstract expressionism especially in the use of banal and literal imagery and the inclusion and the combining of mundane materials into their work.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Eventually by 1963 the movement came to be known worldwide as Pop art.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Pop art is exemplified by artists: Andy Warhol, Claes Oldenburg, Wayne Thiebaud, James Rosenquist, Jim Dine, Tom Wesselmann and Roy Lichtenstein among others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein used oil and Magna paint in his best known works, such as *Drowning Girl* (1963), which was appropriated from the lead story in DC Comics' *Secret Hearts* #83.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] (*Drowning Girl* now is in the collection of Museum of Modern Art, New York.) Also featuring thick outlines, bold colors and Ben-Day dots to represent certain colors, as if created by photographic reproduction.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lichtenstein would say of his own work: Abstract Expressionists "put things down on the canvas and responded to what they had done, to the color positions and sizes.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In October 1962 the Sidney Janis Gallery mounted *The New Realists* the first major Pop art group exhibition in an uptown art gallery in New York City.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Sidney Janis mounted the exhibition in a 57th Street storefront near his gallery at 15 E.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The show sent shockwaves through the New York School and reverberated worldwide.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in the fall of 1962 a historically important and ground-breaking *New Painting of Common Objects* exhibition of Pop art, curated by Walter Hopps at the Pasadena Art Museum sent shock waves across the Western United States.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Campbell's Soup Cans* (sometimes referred to as *32 Campbell's Soup Cans*) is the title of an Andy Warhol work of art that was produced in 1962.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It consists of thirty-two canvases, each measuring 20 inches in height x 16 inches in width (50.8 x 40.6 cm) and each consisting of a painting of a Campbell's Soup can—one of each canned soup variety the company offered at the time.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The individual paintings were produced with a semi-mechanised silkscreen process, using a non-painterly style.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] They helped usher in Pop art as a major art movement that relied on themes from popular culture.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works by Andy Warhol are repetitive and they are made in a non-painterly commercial manner.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Earlier in England in 1956 the term *Pop Art* was used by Lawrence Alloway for paintings that celebrated consumerism of the post World War II era.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement rejected Abstract expressionism and its focus on the hermeneutic and psychological interior, in favor of art which depicted, and often celebrated material consumer culture, advertising, and iconography of the mass production age.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The early works of David Hockney whose paintings emerged from England during the 1960s like *A Bigger Splash,* and the works of Richard Hamilton, Peter Blake, and Eduardo Paolozzi, are considered seminal examples in the movement.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in the downtown scene in New York's East Village 10th Street galleries artists were formulating an American version of Pop art.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Claes Oldenburg had his storefront, and the Green Gallery on 57th Street began to show Tom Wesselmann and James Rosenquist.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later Leo Castelli exhibited other American artists including the bulk of the careers of Andy Warhol and Roy Lichtenstein and his use of Benday dots, a technique used in commercial reproduction and seen in ordinary comic books and in paintings like *Drowning Girl*, 1963, in the gallery above.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] There is a connection between the radical works of Duchamp, and Man Ray, the rebellious Dadaists – with a sense of humor; and Pop Artists like Alex Katz (who became known for his parodies of portrait photography and suburban life), Claes Oldenburg, Andy Warhol, Roy Lichtenstein and the others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1950s and 1960s as abstract painting in America and Europe evolved into movements such as Color Field painting, Post painterly abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Minimal art, shaped canvas painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and the continuation of Abstract expressionism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] 1),* 1963, Oil on canvas, 60 1/4 x 50 1/2 inches, collection: San Francisco Museum of Modern Art), and later in the 1970s Neo-expressionism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bay Area Figurative Movement of whom David Park, Elmer Bischoff, Nathan Oliveira and Richard Diebenkorn whose painting *Cityscape 1,* 1963 is a typical example were influential members flourished during the 1950s and 1960s in California.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Younger painters practiced the use of imagery in new and radical ways.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Yves Klein, Martial Raysse, Niki de Saint Phalle, David Hockney, Alex Katz, Antoni Tàpies, Malcolm Morley, Ralph Goings, Audrey Flack, Richard Estes, Chuck Close, Susan Rothenberg, Eric Fischl, John Baeder, and Vija Celmins were a few who became prominent between the 1960s and the 1980s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fairfield Porter was largely self-taught, and produced representational work in the midst of the Abstract Expressionist movement.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His subjects were primarily landscapes, domestic interiors and portraits of family, friends and fellow artists, many of them affiliated with the New York School of writers, including John Ashbery, Frank O'Hara, and James Schuyler.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many of his paintings were set in or around the family summer house on Great Spruce Head Island, Maine.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-Dada is a movement that started in the 1950s and 1960s and was related to Abstract expressionism only with imagery.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Featuring the emergence of combined manufactured items, with artist materials, moving away from previous conventions of painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This trend in art is exemplified by the work of Jasper Johns and Robert Rauschenberg, whose "combines" in the 1950s were forerunners of Pop Art and Installation art, and made use of the assemblage of large physical objects, including stuffed animals, birds and commercial photography.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s and 1970s abstract painting continued to develop in America through varied styles.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Geometric abstraction, Op art, hard-edge painting, Color Field painting and minimal painting, were some interrelated directions for advanced abstract painting as well as some other new movements.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Morris Louis was an important pioneer in advanced Colorfield painting, his work can serve as a bridge between Abstract expressionism, Colorfield painting, and Minimal Art.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Two influential teachers Josef Albers and Hans Hofmann introduced a new generation of American artists to their advanced theories of color and space.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Josef Albers is best remembered for his work as a Geometric abstractionist painter and theorist.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Most famous are the hundreds of paintings and prints that make up the series *Homage to the Square*.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this rigorous series, begun in 1949, Albers explored chromatic interactions with flat colored squares arranged concentrically on the canvas.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Albers' theories on art and education were formative for the next generation of artists.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His own paintings form the foundation of both hard-edge painting and Op art.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Many Geometric abstract artists, minimalists, and Hard-edge painters elected to use the edges of the image to define the shape of the painting rather than accepting the rectangular format.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In fact, the use of the shaped canvas is primarily associated with paintings of the 1960s and 1970s that are coolly abstract, formalistic, geometrical, objective, rationalistic, clean-lined, brashly sharp-edged, or minimalist in character.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Bykert Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Minimalism and shaped canvas painting in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In 1965, an exhibition called *The Responsive Eye*, curated by William C.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Seitz, was held at the Museum of Modern Art, in New York City.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The works shown were wide-ranging, encompassing the Minimalism of Frank Stella, the Op art of Larry Poons, the work of Alexander Liberman, alongside the masters of the Op Art movement: Victor Vasarely, Richard Anuszkiewicz, Bridget Riley and others.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The exhibition focused on the perceptual aspects of art, which result both from the illusion of movement and the interaction of color relationships.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art, also known as optical art, is a style present in some paintings and other works of art that use optical illusions.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is also closely akin to geometric abstraction and hard-edge painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Although sometimes the term used for it is perceptual abstraction.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art is a method of painting concerning the interaction between illusion and picture plane, between understanding and seeing.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Op art works are abstract, with many of the better known pieces made in only black and white.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] When the viewer looks at them, the impression is given of movement, hidden images, flashing and vibration, patterns, or alternatively, of swelling or warping.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting clearly pointed toward a new direction in American painting, away from abstract expressionism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting is related to Post-painterly abstraction, Suprematism, Abstract Expressionism, Hard-edge painting and Lyrical Abstraction.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Color Field painting sought to rid art of superfluous rhetoric.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Certain artists made references to past or present art, but in general color field painting presents abstraction as an end in itself.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In pursuing this direction of modern art, artists wanted to present each painting as one unified, cohesive, monolithic image.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Frank Stella, Kenneth Noland, Ellsworth Kelly, Barnett Newman, Ronald Davis, Neil Williams, Robert Mangold, Charles Hinman, Richard Tuttle, David Novros, and Alvin Loving are examples of artists associated with the use of the shaped canvas during the period beginning in the early 1960s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] From 1960 Frank Stella produced paintings in aluminium and copper paint and are his first works using shaped canvases (canvases in a shape other than the traditional rectangle or square), often being in L, N, U or T-shapes.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These later developed into more elaborate designs, in the *Irregular Polygon* series (67), for example.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Also in the 1960s, Stella began to use a wider range of colors, typically arranged in straight or curved lines.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Later he began his *Protractor Series* (71) of paintings, in which arcs, sometimes overlapping, within square borders are arranged side-by-side to produce full and half circles painted in rings of concentric color.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] *Harran II,* 1967, is an example of the *Protractor Series*.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These paintings are named after circular cities he had visited while in the Middle East earlier in the 1960s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Irregular Polygon canvases and Protractor series further extended the concept of the shaped canvas.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The Andre Emmerich Gallery, the Leo Castelli Gallery, the Richard Feigen Gallery, and the Park Place Gallery were important showcases for Color Field painting, shaped canvas painting and Lyrical Abstraction in New York City during the 1960s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1960s Color Field painting and Minimal art were often closely associated with each other.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In actuality by the early 1970s both movements became decidedly diverse.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Another related movement of the late 1960s, Lyrical Abstraction (the term being coined by Larry Aldrich, the founder of the Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum, Ridgefield Connecticut), encompassed what Aldrich said he saw in the studios of many artists at that time.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It is also the name of an exhibition that originated in the Aldrich Museum and traveled to the Whitney Museum of American Art and other museums throughout the United States between 1969 and 1971.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Postminimalism often incorporating industrial materials, raw materials, fabrications, found objects, installation, serial repetition, and often with references to Dada and Surrealism is best exemplified in the sculptures of Eva Hesse.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction is a type of freewheeling abstract painting that emerged in the mid-1960s when abstract painters returned to various forms of painterly, pictorial, expressionism with a predominate focus on process, gestalt and repetitive compositional strategies in general.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Lyrical Abstraction shares similarities with Color Field painting and Abstract Expressionism especially in the freewheeling usage of paint – texture and surface.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Direct drawing, calligraphic use of line, the effects of brushed, splattered, stained, squeegeed, poured, and splashed paint superficially resemble the effects seen in Abstract Expressionism and Color Field painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] However the styles are markedly different.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Setting it apart from Abstract Expressionism and Action Painting of the 1940s and 1950s is the approach to composition and drama.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] As seen in Action Painting there is an emphasis on brushstrokes, high compositional drama, dynamic compositional tension.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] While in Lyrical Abstraction as exemplified by the 1971 Ronnie Landfield painting *Garden of Delight* (above), there is a sense of compositional randomness, all over composition, low key and relaxed compositional drama and an emphasis on process, repetition, and an all over sensibility.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Donald Judd had started as a painter, and ended as a creator of objects.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His seminal essay, "Specific Objects" (published in Arts Yearbook 8, 1965), was a touchstone of theory for the formation of Minimalist aesthetics.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In this essay, Judd found a starting point for a new territory for American art, and a simultaneous rejection of residual inherited European artistic values.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He pointed to evidence of this development in the works of an array of artists active in New York at the time, including Jasper Johns, Dan Flavin and Lee Bontecou.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Of "preliminary" importance for Judd was the work of George Earl Ortman, who had concretized and distilled painting's forms into blunt, tough, philosophically charged geometries.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These Specific Objects inhabited a space not then comfortably classifiable as either painting or sculpture.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] That the categorical identity of such objects was itself in question, and that they avoided easy association with well-worn and over-familiar conventions, was a part of their value for Judd.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] American painters such as Brice Marden and Cy Twombly show a clear European influence in their *pure* abstraction, minimalist painting of the 1960s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ronald Davis polyurethane works from the late 1960s pay homage to the *Broken Glass* of Marcel Duchamp.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This movement was heavily criticised by high modernist formalist art critics and historians.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some anxious critics thought Minimalist art represented a misunderstanding of the modern dialectic of painting and sculpture as defined by critic Clement Greenberg, arguably the dominant American critic of painting in the period leading up to the 1960s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The most notable critique of Minimalism was produced by Michael Fried, a Greenbergian critic, who objected to the work on the basis of its "theatricality".
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In *Art and Objecthood* (published in Artforum in June 1967) he declared that the Minimalist work of art, particularly Minimalist sculpture, was based on an engagement with the physicality of the spectator.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] He argued that work like Robert Morris's transformed the act of viewing into a type of spectacle, in which the artifice of the act observation and the viewer's participation in the work were unveiled.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Fried saw this displacement of the viewer's experience from an aesthetic engagement within, to an event outside of the artwork as a failure of Minimal art.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Ad Reinhardt, actually an artist of the Abstract Expressionist generation, but one whose reductive all-black paintings seemed to anticipate minimalism, had this to say about the value of a reductive approach to art: "The more stuff in it, the busier the work of art, the worse it is.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Still other important innovations in abstract painting took place during the 1960s and the 1970s characterized by monochrome painting and hard-edge painting inspired by Ad Reinhardt, Barnett Newman, Milton Resnick, and Ellsworth Kelly.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Artists as diverse as Agnes Martin, Al Held, Larry Zox, Frank Stella, Larry Poons, Brice Marden and others explored the power of simplification.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The convergence of Color Field painting, minimal art, hard-edge painting, Lyrical Abstraction, and postminimalism blurred the distinction between movements that became more apparent in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The neo-expressionism movement is related to earlier developments in abstract expressionism, neo-Dada, Lyrical Abstraction and postminimal painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These works were inspirational to a new generation of painters interested in a revival of expressive imagery.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] His painting *Painting, Smoking, Eating* 1973, seen above in the gallery is an example of Guston's final and conclusive return to representation.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] In the late 1970s and early 1980s, there was also a return to painting that occurred almost simultaneously in Italy, Germany, France and Britain.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These movements were called Transavantguardia, Neue Wilde, Figuration Libre, Neo-expressionism, the school of London, and in the late 1990s the Stuckists, a group that emerged late in 1990s respectively.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] These painting were characterized by large formats, free expressive mark making, figuration, myth and imagination.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] All work in this genre came to be labeled neo-expressionism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Some critics regarded it as driven by profit motivations by large commercial galleries.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] This type of art continues in popularity into the 21st century, even after the art crash of the late 1980s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the late 1970s in the United States painters who began working with invigorated surfaces and who returned to imagery like Susan Rothenberg gained in popularity, especially as seen above in paintings like *Horse 2,* 1979.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] During the 1980s American artists like Eric Fischl, David Salle, Jean-Michel Basquiat (who began as a graffiti artist), Julian Schnabel, and Keith Haring, and Italian painters like Mimmo Paladino, Sandro Chia, and Enzo Cucchi, among others defined the idea of Neo-expressionism in America.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionism was a style of modern painting that became popular in the late 1970s and dominated the art market until the mid-1980s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] It developed in Europe as a reaction against the conceptual and minimalistic art of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Neo-expressionists returned to portraying recognizable objects, such as the human body (although sometimes in a virtually abstract manner), in a rough and violently emotional way using vivid colours and banal colour harmonies.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] The veteran painters Philip Guston, Frank Auerbach, Leon Kossoff, Gerhard Richter, A.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Penck and Georg Baselitz, along with slightly younger artists like Anselm Kiefer, Eric Fischl, Susan Rothenberg, Francesco Clemente, Damien Hirst, Jean-Michel Basquiat, Julian Schnabel, Keith Haring, and many others became known for working in this intense expressionist vein of painting.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] At the beginning of the 21st century Contemporary painting and Contemporary art in general continues in several contiguous modes, characterized by the idea of pluralism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] Mainstream painting has been rejected by artists of the postmodern era in favor of artistic pluralism.
[src:ancient-rome/20th-century-western-painting-p02] According to art critic Arthur Danto there is an *anything goes* attitude that prevails; an "everything going on", and consequently "nothing going on" syndrome; this creates an aesthetic traffic jam with no firm and clear direction and with every lane on the artistic superhighway filled to capacity.
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] The program started in 1947 as the "Plan to Effect Standardization" between the armies of the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada (the ABC Armies), with the three nations looking to capitalize on the close cooperation between the forces during World War II.
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] In 1954, the Plan was replaced by the "Basic Standardization Concept".
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] Australia joined the organization in 1963, and the ABCA Program was established with the ratification of the "Basic Standardization Agreement 1964" on 1 October 1964.
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] In 1965, Australia successfully sponsored the introduction of New Zealand to the agreement as an observer.
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] Originally, the role of ABCANZ was limited to issues of standardization for soldier equipment, training, and tactics.
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] Following the September 11 attacks, a review by the Program's Heads of Delegations saw the Program modified to address the changing security environment and improve responsiveness, relevance, and focus on interoperability.
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] The overhaul was completed by June 2004.
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] Also in 2004, the increasing involvement of the United States Marine Corps was formally recognized with a Memorandum of Understanding between the Corps and the United States Army, allowing both forces to be represented by a single position.
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] Following this, the United Kingdom delegation successfully incorporated the Royal Marines.
[src:ancient-rome/abcanz-armies] New Zealand became a full member of ABCA in early 2006.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In modern historiography, **ancient Rome** is the Roman civilisation from the founding of the Italian city of Rome in the 8th century BC to the collapse of the Western Roman Empire in the 5th century AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] It encompasses the Roman Kingdom (753–509 BC), the Roman Republic (509‍–‍27 BC), and the Roman Empire (27 BC – 476 AD) until the fall of the western empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome began as an Italic settlement, traditionally dated to 753 BC, beside the River Tiber in the Italian Peninsula.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The settlement grew into the city and polity of Rome, and came to control its neighbours through a combination of treaties and military strength.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] It eventually controlled the Italian Peninsula, assimilating the Greek culture of southern Italy (Magna Graecia) and the Etruscan culture, and then became the dominant power in the Mediterranean region and parts of Europe.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] At its height it controlled the North African coast, Egypt, Southern Europe, and most of Western Europe, the Balkans, Crimea, and much of the Middle East, including Anatolia, the Levant, and parts of Mesopotamia and Arabia.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] That empire was among the largest empires in the ancient world, covering around 5 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles) in AD 117, with an estimated 50 to 90 million inhabitants, roughly 20% of the world's population at the time.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman state evolved from an elective monarchy to a classical republic and then to an increasingly autocratic military dictatorship during the Empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Rome is often grouped into classical antiquity together with ancient Greece, and their similar cultures and societies are known as the Greco-Roman world.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Ancient Roman civilisation has contributed to modern language, religion, society, technology, law, politics, government, warfare, art, literature, architecture, and engineering.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Rome professionalised and expanded its military and created a system of government called *res publica*, the inspiration for modern republics such as the United States and France.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] It achieved impressive technological and architectural feats, such as the empire-wide construction of aqueducts and roads, as well as more grandiose monuments and facilities.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence of settlement around Rome starts to emerge c.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Large-scale organisation appears only c.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] 800 BC, with the first graves in the Esquiline Hill's necropolis, along with a clay and timber wall on the bottom of the Palatine Hill dating to the middle of the 8th century BC.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] 650 BC, the Romans started to drain the valley between the Capitoline and Palatine Hills, where today sits the Roman Forum.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] By the 6th century BC, the Romans were constructing the Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus on the Capitoline and expanding to the Forum Boarium located between the Capitoline and Aventine Hills.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans themselves had a founding myth, attributing their city to Romulus and Remus, offspring of Mars and a princess of the mythical city of Alba Longa.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The sons, sentenced to death, were rescued by a wolf and returned to restore the Alban king and found a city.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] After a dispute, Romulus killed Remus and became the city's sole founder.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The area of his initial settlement on the Palatine Hill was later known as Roma quadrata ('Square Rome').
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The story dates at least to the 3rd century BC, and the later Roman antiquarian Marcus Terentius Varro placed the city's foundation to 753 BC.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Another legend, recorded by Greek historian Dionysius of Halicarnassus, says that Prince Aeneas led a group of Trojans on a sea voyage to found a new Troy after the Trojan War.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] They landed on the banks of the Tiber River and a woman travelling with them, Roma, torched their ships to prevent them from leaving again.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman poet Virgil recounted this legend in his classical epic poem the *Aeneid*.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Literary and archaeological evidence is clear on there having been kings in Rome, attested in fragmentary 6th-century BC texts.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Long after the abolition of the Roman monarchy, a vestigial *rex sacrorum* was retained to exercise the monarch's former priestly functions.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans believed that their monarchy was elective, with seven legendary kings who were largely unrelated by blood.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Evidence of Roman expansion is clear in the 6th century BC; by its end, Rome controlled a territory of some 780 square kilometres (300 square miles) with a population perhaps as high as 35,000.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] 625 BC; the Romans attributed the creation of their first popular organisations and the Senate to the regal period as well.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Rome also started to extend its control over its Latin neighbours.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] While later Roman stories like the *Aeneid* asserted that all Latins descended from the character Aeneas, a common culture is attested to archaeologically.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Attested to reciprocal rights of marriage and citizenship between Latin cities—the *Jus Latii*—along with shared religious festivals, further indicate a shared culture.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century, most of this area had become dominated by the Romans.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the 6th century BC, Rome and many of its Italian neighbours entered a period of turbulence.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Archaeological evidence implies some degree of large-scale warfare.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] According to tradition and later writers such as Livy, the Roman Republic was established c.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] 509 BC, when the last of the seven kings of Rome, Tarquin the Proud, was deposed and a system based on annually elected magistrates and various representative assemblies was established.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] A constitution set a series of checks and balances, and a separation of powers.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The most important magistrates were the two consuls, who together exercised executive authority such as *imperium*, or military command.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The consuls had to work with the Senate, which was initially an advisory council of the ranking nobility, or patricians, but grew in size and power.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Other magistrates of the Republic include tribunes, quaestors, aediles, praetors and censors.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The magistracies were originally restricted to patricians, but were later opened to common people, or plebeians.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Republican voting assemblies included the *comitia centuriata* ('centuriate assembly'), which voted on matters of war and peace and elected men to the most important offices, and the *comitia tributa* ('tribal assembly'), which elected less important offices.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In the 4th century BC, Rome had come under attack by the Gauls, who now extended their power in the Italian peninsula beyond the Po Valley and through Etruria.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] On 16 July 390 BC, a Gallic army under the leadership of tribal chieftain Brennus, defeated the Romans at the Battle of the Allia and marched to Rome.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls looted and burned the city, then laid siege to the Capitoline Hill, where some Romans had barricaded themselves, for seven months.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Gauls then agreed to give the Romans peace in exchange for 1000 pounds of gold.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] According to later legend, the Roman supervising the weighing noticed that the Gauls were using false scales.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans then took up arms and defeated the Gauls.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans gradually subdued the other peoples on the Italian peninsula, including the Etruscans.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The last threat to Roman hegemony in Italy came when Tarentum, a major Greek colony, enlisted the aid of Pyrrhus of Epirus in 281 BC, but this effort failed as well.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Romans secured their conquests by founding Roman colonies in strategic areas, thereby establishing stable control over the region.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In the 3rd century BC Rome faced a new and formidable opponent: Carthage, the other major power in the Western Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The First Punic War began in 264 BC, when the city of Messana asked for Carthage's help in their conflicts with Hiero II of Syracuse.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] After the Carthaginian intercession, Messana asked Rome to expel the Carthaginians.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Rome entered this war because Syracuse and Messana were too close to the newly conquered Greek cities of Southern Italy and Carthage was now able to make an offensive through Roman territory; along with this, Rome could extend its domain over Sicily.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage was a maritime power, and the Roman lack of ships and naval experience made the path to the victory a long and difficult one for the Roman Republic.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Despite this, after more than 20 years of war, Rome defeated Carthage and a peace treaty was signed.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Among the reasons for the Second Punic War was the subsequent war reparations Carthage acquiesced to at the end of the First Punic War.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The war began with the audacious invasion of Hispania by Hannibal, who marched through Hispania to the Italian Alps.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Hannibal's invasion lasted over 16 years, ravaging Italy, but ultimately Carthage was defeated in the decisive Battle of Zama in October 202 BC.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] More than a half century after these events, Carthage was left humiliated and the Republic's focus was now directed towards the Hellenistic kingdoms of Greece and revolts in Hispania.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] However, Carthage, having paid the war indemnity, felt that its commitments and submission to Rome had ceased, a vision not shared by the Roman Senate.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Third Punic War began when Rome declared war against Carthage in 149 BC.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Carthage resisted well at the first strike but could not withstand the attack of Scipio Aemilianus, who entirely destroyed the city, enslaved all the citizens and gained control of that region, which became the province of Africa.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] All these wars resulted in Rome's first overseas conquests (Sicily, Hispania and Africa) and the rise of Rome as a significant imperial power.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating the Macedonian and Seleucid Empires in the 2nd century BC, the Romans became the dominant people of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The conquest of the Hellenistic kingdoms brought the Roman and Greek cultures in closer contact and the Roman elite, once rural, became cosmopolitan.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Foreign dominance led to internal strife.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Senators became rich at the provinces' expense; soldiers, who were mostly small-scale farmers, were away from home longer and could not maintain their land; and the increased reliance on foreign slaves and the growth of *latifundia* reduced the availability of paid work.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Income from war booty, mercantilism in the new provinces, and tax farming created new economic opportunities for the wealthy, forming a new class of merchants, called the equestrians.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The **lex Claudia** forbade members of the Senate from engaging in commerce, so while the equestrians could theoretically join the Senate, they were severely restricted in political power.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate squabbled perpetually, repeatedly blocked important land reforms and refused to give the equestrian class a larger say in the government.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Violent gangs of the urban unemployed, controlled by rival Senators, intimidated the electorate through violence.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The situation came to a head in the late 2nd century BC under the Gracchi brothers, a pair of tribunes who attempted to pass land reform legislation that would redistribute the major patrician landholdings among the plebeians.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Both brothers were killed and the Senate passed reforms reversing the Gracchi brother's actions.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] This led to the growing divide of the plebeian groups (*populares*) and equestrian classes (*optimates*).
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Gaius Marius soon became a leader of the Republic, holding the first of his seven consulships (an unprecedented number) in 107 BC by arguing that his former patron Quintus Caecilius Metellus Numidicus was not able to defeat and capture the Numidian king Jugurtha.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Marius then started his military reform: in his recruitment to fight Jugurtha, he levied the very poor (an innovation), and many landless men entered the army.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Marius was elected for five consecutive consulships from 104 to 100 BC, as Rome needed a military leader to defeat the Cimbri and the Teutones, who were threatening Rome.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] After Marius's retirement, Rome had a brief peace, during which the Italian *socii* ('allies') requested Roman citizenship and voting rights.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The reformist Marcus Livius Drusus supported their legal process but was assassinated, and the *socii* revolted against the Romans in the Social War.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] At one point both consuls were killed; Marius was appointed to command the army together with Lucius Julius Caesar and Lucius Cornelius Sulla.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Social War, Marius and Sulla were the premier military men in Rome and their partisans were in conflict, both sides jostling for power.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 88 BC, Sulla was elected for his first consulship and his first assignment was to defeat Mithridates VI of Pontus, whose intentions were to conquer the Eastern part of the Roman territories.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] However, Marius's partisans managed his installation to the military command, defying Sulla and the Senate.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] To consolidate his own power, Sulla conducted a surprising and illegal action: he marched to Rome with his legions, killing all those who showed support to Marius's cause.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In the following year, 87 BC, Marius, who had fled at Sulla's march, returned to Rome while Sulla was campaigning in Greece.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He seized power along with the consul Lucius Cornelius Cinna and killed the other consul, Gnaeus Octavius, achieving his seventh consulship.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Marius and Cinna revenged their partisans by conducting a massacre.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Marius died in 86 BC, due to age and poor health, just a few months after seizing power.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Cinna exercised absolute power until his death in 84 BC.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] After returning from his Eastern campaigns, Sulla had a free path to reestablish his own power.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 83 BC he made his second march on Rome and began a time of terror: thousands of nobles, knights and senators were executed.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla held two dictatorships and one more consulship, which began the crisis and decline of Roman Republic.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In the mid-1st century BC, Roman politics were restless.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Political divisions in Rome split into one of two groups, *populares* (who hoped for the support of the people) and *optimates* (the 'best', who wanted to maintain exclusive aristocratic control).
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Sulla overthrew all populist leaders and his constitutional reforms removed powers (such as those of the tribune of the plebs) that had supported populist approaches.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Meanwhile, social and economic stresses continued to build; Rome had become a metropolis with a super-rich aristocracy, debt-ridden aspirants, and a large proletariat often of impoverished farmers.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The latter groups supported the Catilinarian conspiracy—a resounding failure since the consul Marcus Tullius Cicero quickly arrested and executed the main leaders.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Julius Caesar reconciled the two most powerful men in Rome: Marcus Licinius Crassus, who had financed much of his earlier career, and Crassus' rival, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus (anglicised as Pompey), to whom he married his daughter.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He formed them into a new informal alliance including himself, the First Triumvirate ('three men').
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's daughter died in childbirth in 54 BC, and in 53 BC, Crassus invaded Parthia and was killed in the Battle of Carrhae; the Triumvirate disintegrated.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar conquered Gaul, obtained immense wealth, respect in Rome and the loyalty of battle-hardened legions.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He became a threat to Pompey and was loathed by many *optimates*.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Confident that Caesar could be stopped by legal means, Pompey's party tried to strip Caesar of his legions, a prelude to Caesar's trial, impoverishment, and exile.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] To avoid this fate, Caesar crossed the Rubicon River and invaded Rome in 49 BC.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Battle of Pharsalus was a brilliant victory for Caesar and in this and other campaigns, he destroyed all of the *optimates* leaders: Metellus Scipio, Cato the Younger, and Pompey's son, Gnaeus Pompeius Magnus.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar was now pre-eminent over Rome: in five years he held four consulships, two ordinary dictatorships, and two special dictatorships, one for perpetuity.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered in 44 BC, on the Ides of March by the *Liberatores*.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Caesar's assassination caused political and social turmoil in Rome; the city was ruled by his friend and colleague, Mark Antony.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Soon afterward, Octavian, whom Caesar adopted through his will, arrived in Rome.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian (historians regard Octavius as Octavian due to the Roman naming conventions) tried to align himself with the Caesarian faction.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 43 BC, along with Antony and Marcus Aemilius Lepidus, Caesar's best friend, he legally established the Second Triumvirate.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Upon its formation, 130–300 senators were executed, and their property was confiscated, due to their supposed support for the *Liberatores*.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 42 BC, the Senate deified Caesar as *Divus Iulius*; Octavian thus became *Divi filius*, the son of the deified.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In the same year, Octavian and Antony defeated both Caesar's assassins and the leaders of the *Liberatores*, Marcus Junius Brutus and Gaius Cassius Longinus, in the Battle of Philippi.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate was marked by the proscriptions of many senators and *equites*: after a revolt led by Antony's brother Lucius Antonius, more than 300 senators and *equites* involved were executed, although Lucius was spared.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Triumvirate divided the Empire among the triumvirs: Lepidus was given charge of Africa, Antony, the eastern provinces, and Octavian remained in Italia and controlled Hispania and Gaul.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Triumvirate expired in 38 BC but was renewed for five more years.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] However, the relationship between Octavian and Antony had deteriorated, and Lepidus was forced to retire in 36 BC after betraying Octavian in Sicily.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] By the end of the Triumvirate, Antony was living in Ptolemaic Egypt, ruled by his lover, Cleopatra VII.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Antony's affair with Cleopatra was seen as an act of treason, since she was queen of another country.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Additionally, Antony adopted a lifestyle considered too extravagant and Hellenistic for a Roman statesman.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Following Antony's Donations of Alexandria, which gave to Cleopatra the title of "Queen of Kings", and to Antony's and Cleopatra's children the regal titles to the newly conquered Eastern territories, war between Octavian and Antony broke out.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Octavian annihilated Egyptian forces in the Battle of Actium in 31 BC.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Now Egypt was conquered by the Roman Empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 27 BC and at the age of 36, Octavian was the sole Roman leader.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In that year, he took the name *Augustus*.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] That event is usually taken by historians as the beginning of Roman Empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Officially, the government was republican, but Augustus assumed absolute powers.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His reform of the government brought about a two-century period colloquially referred to by Romans as the Pax Romana.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudian dynasty was established by Augustus.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The emperors of this dynasty were Augustus, Tiberius, Caligula, Claudius and Nero.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians started the destruction of republican values, but on the other hand, they boosted Rome's status as the central power in the Mediterranean region.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] While Caligula and Nero are usually remembered in popular culture as dysfunctional emperors, Augustus and Claudius are remembered as successful in politics and the military.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] This dynasty instituted imperial tradition in Rome and frustrated any attempt to reestablish a Republic.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] 27 BC – AD 14) gathered almost all the republican powers under his official title, *princeps*, and diminished the political influence of the senatorial class by boosting the equestrian class.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The senators lost their right to rule certain provinces, like Egypt, since the governor of that province was directly nominated by the emperor.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The creation of the Praetorian Guard and his reforms in the military, creating a standing army with a fixed size of 28 legions, ensured his total control over the army.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Compared with the Second Triumvirate's epoch, Augustus' reign as *princeps* was very peaceful, which led the people and the nobles of Rome to support Augustus, increasing his strength in political affairs.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His generals were responsible for the field command, gaining such commanders as Marcus Vipsanius Agrippa, Nero Claudius Drusus and Germanicus much respect from the populace and the legions.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus intended to extend the Roman Empire to the whole known world, and in his reign, Rome conquered Cantabria, Aquitania, Raetia, Dalmatia, Illyricum and Pannonia.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Under Augustus' reign, Roman literature grew steadily in what is known as the Golden Age of Latin Literature.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Poets like Virgil, Horace, Ovid and Rufus developed a rich literature, and were close friends of Augustus.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Along with Maecenas, he sponsored patriotic poems, such as Virgil's epic *Aeneid* and historiographical works like those of Livy.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus continued the changes to the calendar promoted by Caesar, and the month of August is named after him.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Augustus brought a peaceful and thriving era to Rome, known as *Pax Romana*.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Julio-Claudians continued to rule Rome after Augustus' death in 14 AD and remained in power until the death of Nero in 68 AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Influenced by his wife, Livia Drusilla, Augustus appointed her son from another marriage, Tiberius, as his heir.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Senate agreed with the succession, and granted to Tiberius the same titles and honours once granted to Augustus: the title of *princeps* and *Pater patriae*, and the Civic Crown.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] However, Tiberius was not an enthusiast for political affairs: after agreement with the Senate, he retired to Capri in 26 AD, and left control of the city of Rome in the hands of the praetorian prefect Sejanus (until 31 AD) and Macro (from 31 to 37 AD).
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The male line of the Julio-Claudians was limited to Tiberius' nephew Claudius, his grandson Tiberius Gemellus and his grand-nephew Caligula.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] As Gemellus was still a child, Caligula was chosen to rule the empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He was a popular leader in the first half of his reign, but became a crude and insane tyrant in his years controlling government.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Praetorian Guard murdered Caligula four years after the death of Tiberius, and, with belated support from the senators, proclaimed his uncle Claudius as the new emperor.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was not as authoritarian as Tiberius and Caligula.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius conquered Lycia and Thrace; his most important deed was the beginning of the conquest of Britannia.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Claudius was poisoned by his wife, Agrippina the Younger in 54 AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His heir was Nero, son of Agrippina and her former husband, since Claudius' son Britannicus had not reached manhood upon his father's death.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Nero sent his general, Suetonius Paulinus, to invade modern-day Wales, where he encountered stiff resistance.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Celts there were independent, tough, resistant to tax collectors, and fought Paulinus as he battled his way across from east to west.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] It took him a long time to reach the north-west coast, and in 60 AD he finally crossed the Menai Strait to the sacred island of Mona (Anglesey), the last stronghold of the druids.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His soldiers attacked the island and massacred the druids: men, women and children, destroyed the shrine and the sacred groves and threw many of the sacred standing stones into the sea.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] While Paulinus and his troops were massacring druids in Mona, the tribes of modern-day East Anglia staged a revolt led by queen Boadicea of the Iceni.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The rebels sacked and burned Camulodunum, Londinium and Verulamium (modern-day Colchester, London and St Albans respectively) before they were crushed by Paulinus.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Boadicea, like Cleopatra before her, committed suicide to avoid the disgrace of being paraded in triumph in Rome.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Nero is widely known as the first persecutor of Christians and for the Great Fire of Rome, rumoured to have been started by the emperor himself.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] A conspiracy against Nero in 65 AD under Calpurnius Piso failed, but in 68 AD the armies under Julius Vindex in Gaul and Servius Sulpicius Galba in modern-day Spain revolted.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Deserted by the Praetorian Guards and condemned to death by the senate, Nero killed himself.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Flavians were the second dynasty to rule Rome.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] By 68 AD, the year of Nero's death, there was no chance of a return to the Republic, and so a new emperor had to arise.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] After the turmoil in the Year of the Four Emperors, Titus Flavius Vespasianus (anglicised as Vespasian) took control of the empire and established a new dynasty.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Under the Flavians, Rome continued its expansion, and the state remained secure.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The most significant military campaign undertaken during the Flavian period was the siege and destruction of Jerusalem in 70 AD by Titus.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The destruction of the city was the culmination of the Roman campaign in Judea following the Jewish uprising of 66 AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Second Temple was completely demolished, after which Titus' soldiers proclaimed him *imperator* in honour of the victory.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Jerusalem was sacked and much of the population killed or dispersed.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Josephus claims that 1,100,000 people were killed during the siege, of whom a majority were Jewish, and 97,000 were captured and enslaved.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Many fled to areas around the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was a general under Claudius and Nero and fought as a commander in the First Jewish-Roman War.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Following the turmoil of the Year of the Four Emperors, in 69 AD, four emperors were enthroned in turn: Galba, Otho, Vitellius, and, lastly, Vespasian, who crushed Vitellius' forces and became emperor.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He reconstructed many buildings which were uncompleted, like a statue of Apollo and the temple of *Divus Claudius* ("the deified Claudius"), both initiated by Nero.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Buildings destroyed by the Great Fire of Rome were rebuilt, and he revitalised the Capitol.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian started the construction of the Flavian Amphitheater, commonly known as the Colosseum.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The historians Josephus and Pliny the Elder wrote their works during Vespasian's reign.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian was Josephus' sponsor and Pliny dedicated his *Naturalis Historia* to Titus, son of Vespasian.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Vespasian sent legions to defend the eastern frontier in Cappadocia, extended the occupation in Britannia (modern-day England, Wales and southern Scotland) and reformed the tax system.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He finished the Flavian Amphitheater, using war spoils from the First Jewish-Roman War, and hosted victory games that lasted for a hundred days.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] These games included gladiatorial combats, horse races and a sensational mock naval battle on the flooded grounds of the Colosseum.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Titus died of fever in 81 AD, and was succeeded by his brother Domitian.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] As emperor, Domitian showed the characteristics of a tyrant.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He ruled for fifteen years, during which time he acquired a reputation for self-promotion as a living god.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed at least two temples in honour of Jupiter, the supreme deity in Roman religion.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He was murdered following a plot within his own household.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Following Domitian's murder, the Senate rapidly appointed Nerva as Emperor.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva had noble ancestry, and he had served as an advisor to Nero and the Flavians.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His rule restored many of the traditional liberties of Rome's upper classes, which Domitian had over-ridden.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva–Antonine dynasty from 96 AD to 192 AD included the "five good emperors" Nerva, Trajan, Hadrian, Antoninus Pius and Marcus Aurelius.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Nerva-Antonine dynasty came to an end with Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Nerva abdicated and died in 98 AD, and was succeeded by the general Trajan.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan is credited with the restoration of traditional privileges and rights of commoner and senatorial classes, which later Roman historians claim to have been eroded during Domitian's autocracy.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan fought three Dacian wars, winning territories roughly equivalent to modern-day Romania and Moldova.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He undertook an ambitious public building program in Rome, including Trajan's Forum, Trajan's Market and Trajan's Column, with the architect Apollodorus of Damascus.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He remodelled the Pantheon and extended the Circus Maximus.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia appointed a king for Armenia without consulting Rome, Trajan declared war on Parthia and deposed the king of Armenia.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 115 he took the Northern Mesopotamian cities of Nisibis and Batnae, organised a province of Mesopotamia (116), and issued coins that claimed Armenia and Mesopotamia were under the authority of the Roman people.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year, he captured Seleucia and the Parthian capital Ctesiphon (near modern Baghdad).
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] After defeating a Parthian revolt and a Jewish revolt, he withdrew due to health issues, and in 117, he died of edema.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Under Trajan, the Roman Empire had reached the peak of its territorial expansion.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Rome's dominion now spanned 5.0 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles).
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Trajan's successor Hadrian withdrew all the troops stationed in Parthia, Armenia and Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq), abandoning Trajan's conquests.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian's army crushed a revolt in Mauretania and the Bar Kokhba revolt in Judea.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] This was the last large-scale Jewish revolt against the Romans, and was suppressed with massive repercussions in Judea.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Hundreds of thousands of Jews were killed.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian renamed the province of Judea "Provincia Syria Palaestina", after one of Judea's most hated enemies.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He constructed fortifications and walls, like the celebrated Hadrian's Wall which separated Roman Britannia and the tribes of modern-day Scotland.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Hadrian promoted culture, especially the Greek.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He forbade torture and humanised the laws.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His many building projects included aqueducts, baths, libraries and theatres; additionally, he travelled nearly every province in the Empire to review military and infrastructural conditions.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Following Hadrian's death in 138 AD, his successor Antoninus Pius built temples, theatres, and mausoleums, promoted the arts and sciences, and bestowed honours and financial rewards upon the teachers of rhetoric and philosophy.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] On becoming emperor, Antoninus made few initial changes, leaving intact as far as possible the arrangements instituted by his predecessor.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Antoninus expanded Roman Britannia by invading what is now southern Scotland and building the Antonine Wall.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He also continued Hadrian's policy of humanising the laws.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His reign was the most peaceful in the entire history of Roman Empire, he left "an empire in very fine shape.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] It was a height that, arguably, it would never reach again." He died in 161 AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Marcus Aurelius, known as the Philosopher, was the last of the Five Good Emperors.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He was a stoic philosopher and wrote the *Meditations*.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He defeated barbarian tribes in the Marcomannic Wars as well as the Parthian Empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His co-emperor, Lucius Verus, died in 169 AD, probably from the Antonine Plague, a pandemic that killed nearly five million people through the Empire in 165–180 AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] From Nerva to Marcus Aurelius, the empire achieved an unprecedented status.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The powerful influence of laws and manners had gradually cemented the union of the provinces.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] All the citizens enjoyed and abused the advantages of wealth.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The image of a free constitution was preserved with decent reverence.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Roman senate appeared to possess the sovereign authority, and devolved on the emperors all the executive powers of government.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Gibbon declared the rule of these "Five Good Emperors" the golden era of the Empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] During this time, Rome reached its greatest territorial extent.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus, son of Marcus Aurelius, became emperor after his father's death.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He is not counted as one of the Five Good Emperors, due to his direct kinship with the latter emperor; in addition, he was militarily passive.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Commodus was killed by a conspiracy involving Quintus Aemilius Laetus and his wife Marcia in late 192 AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The following year is known as the Year of the Five Emperors, during which Helvius Pertinax, Didius Julianus, Pescennius Niger, Clodius Albinus and Septimius Severus held the imperial dignity.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Pertinax, a member of the senate who had been one of Marcus Aurelius's right-hand men, was the choice of Laetus, and he ruled vigorously and judiciously.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Laetus soon became jealous and instigated Pertinax's murder by the Praetorian Guard, who then auctioned the empire to the highest bidder, Didius Julianus, for 25,000 sesterces per man.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The people of Rome were appalled and appealed to the frontier legions to save them.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The legions of three frontier provinces—Britannia, Pannonia Superior, and Syria—resented being excluded from the "donative" and replied by declaring their individual generals to be emperor.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Lucius Septimius Severus Geta, the Pannonian commander, bribed the opposing forces, pardoned the Praetorian Guards and installed himself as emperor.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He and his successors governed with the legions' support.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The changes on coinage and military expenditures were the root of the financial crisis that marked the Crisis of the Third Century.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Severus was enthroned after invading Rome and having Didius Julianus killed.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Severus attempted to revive totalitarianism and, addressing the Roman people and Senate, praised the severity and cruelty of Marius and Sulla, which worried the senators.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] When Parthia invaded Roman territory, Severus successfully waged war against that country.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Notwithstanding this military success, Severus failed in invading Hatra, a rich Arabian city.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Severus killed his legate, who was gaining respect from the legions; and his soldiers fell victim to famine.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] After this disastrous campaign, he withdrew.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Severus also intended to vanquish the whole of Britannia.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] To achieve this, he waged war against the Caledonians.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] However, he became ill and died in 211 AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His sons Caracalla and Geta were made emperors.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Caracalla had his brother, a youth, assassinated in his mother's arms, and may have murdered 20,000 of Geta's followers.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He continued Severus' policy and gained respect from the legions.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Knowing that the citizens of Alexandria disliked him and were denigrating his character, Caracalla served a banquet for its notable citizens, after which his soldiers killed all the guests.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] From the security of the temple of Sarapis, he then directed an indiscriminate slaughter of Alexandria's people.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 212, he issued the Edict of Caracalla, giving full Roman citizenship to all free men living in the Empire, with the exception of the *dediticii*, people who had become subject to Rome through surrender in war, and freed slaves.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Mary Beard points to the edict as a fundamental turning point, after which *Rome* was "effectively a new state masquerading under an old name".
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus conspired to have Caracalla assassinated by one of his soldiers during a pilgrimage to the Temple of the Moon in Carrhae, in 217 AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Macrinus assumed power, but soon removed himself from Rome to the east and Antioch.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His brief reign ended in 218, when the youngster Bassianus, high priest of the temple of the Sun at Emesa, and supposedly illegitimate son of Caracalla, was declared Emperor by the disaffected soldiers of Macrinus.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted the name of Antoninus but history has named him after his Sun god Elagabalus, represented on Earth in the form of a large black stone.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] An incompetent and lascivious ruler, Elagabalus adopted his cousin Severus Alexander, as Caesar, but subsequently grew jealous and attempted to assassinate him.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] However, the Praetorian guard preferred Alexander, murdered Elagabalus, dragged his mutilated corpse through the streets of Rome, and threw it into the Tiber.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Alexander waged war against many foes, including the revitalised Persia and also the Germanic peoples, who invaded Gaul.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His losses generated dissatisfaction among his soldiers, and some of them murdered him during his Germanic campaign in 235 AD.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] A disastrous scenario emerged after the death of Alexander Severus: the Roman state was plagued by civil wars, external invasions, political chaos, pandemics and economic depression.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The old Roman values had fallen, and Mithraism and Christianity had begun to spread through the populace.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Emperors were no longer men linked with nobility; they usually were born in lower-classes of distant parts of the Empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] These men rose to prominence through military ranks, and became emperors through civil wars.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] There were 26 emperors in a 49-year period, a signal of political instability.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Maximinus Thrax was the first ruler of that time, governing for just three years.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Others ruled just for a few months, like Gordian I, Gordian II, Balbinus and Hostilian.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The population and the frontiers were abandoned, since the emperors were mostly concerned with defeating rivals and establishing their power.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The economy also suffered: massive military expenditures from the Severi caused a devaluation of Roman coins.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Hyperinflation came at this time as well.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Plague of Cyprian broke out in 250 and killed a huge portion of the population.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 260 AD, the provinces of Syria Palaestina, Asia Minor and Egypt separated from the rest of the Roman state to form the Palmyrene Empire, ruled by Queen Zenobia and centered on Palmyra.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In that same year the Gallic Empire was created by Postumus, retaining Britannia and Gaul.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] These countries separated from Rome after the capture of emperor Valerian by the Sassanids of Persia, the first Roman ruler to be captured by his enemies; it was a humiliating fact for the Romans.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis began to recede during the reigns of Claudius Gothicus (268–270), who defeated the Gothic invaders, and Aurelian (271–275), who reconquered both the Gallic and Palmyrene Empires.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The crisis was overcome during the reign of Diocletian.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 284 AD, Diocletian was hailed as Imperator by the eastern army.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian healed the empire from the crisis, by political and economic shifts.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] A new form of government was established: the Tetrarchy.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The Empire was divided among four emperors, two in the West and two in the East.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The first tetrarchs were Diocletian (in the East), Maximian (in the West), and two junior emperors, Galerius (in the East) and Flavius Constantius (in the West).
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] To adjust the economy, Diocletian made several tax reforms.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian expelled the Persians who plundered Syria and conquered some barbarian tribes with Maximian.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He adopted many behaviours of Eastern monarchs.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Anyone in the presence of the emperor had now to prostrate himself—a common act in the East, but never practised in Rome before.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian did not use a disguised form of Republic, as the other emperors since Augustus had done.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Between 290 and 330, half a dozen new capitals had been established by the members of the Tetrarchy, officially or not: Antioch, Nicomedia, Thessalonike, Sirmium, Milan, and Trier.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian was also responsible for a significant Christian persecution.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 303 he and Galerius started the persecution and ordered the destruction of all the Christian churches and scripts and forbade Christian worship.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Diocletian abdicated in 305 AD together with Maximian, thus, he was the first Roman emperor to resign.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] His reign ended the traditional form of imperial rule, the Principate (from princeps) and started the Tetrarchy.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine assumed the empire as a tetrarch in 306.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He conducted many wars against the other tetrarchs.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 313, he issued the Edict of Milan, which granted liberty for Christians to profess their religion.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine was converted to Christianity, enforcing the Christian faith.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He began the Christianization of the Empire and of Europe—a process concluded by the Catholic Church in the Middle Ages.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] He was defeated by the Franks and the Alamanni during 306–308.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 324 he defeated another tetrarch, Licinius, and controlled all the empire, as it was before Diocletian.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] To celebrate his victories and Christianity's relevance, he rebuilt Byzantium and renamed it Nova Roma ("New Rome"); but the city soon gained the informal name of Constantinople ("City of Constantine").
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The reign of Julian, who under the influence of his adviser Mardonius attempted to restore Classical Roman and Hellenistic religion, only briefly interrupted the succession of Christian emperors.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Constantinople served as a new capital for the Empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In fact, Rome had lost its central importance since the Crisis of the Third Century—Mediolanum was the western capital from 286 to 330, until the reign of Honorius, when Ravenna was made capital, in the 5th century.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] Constantine's administrative and monetary reforms, that reunited the Empire under one emperor, and rebuilt the city of Byzantium, as Constantinopolis Nova Roma, changed the high period of the ancient world.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In the late 4th and 5th centuries the Western Empire entered a critical stage which terminated with the fall of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The next emperor, Theodosius I (379–395), gave even more force to the Christian faith, and after his death, the Empire was divided into the Eastern Roman Empire, ruled by Arcadius and the Western Roman Empire, commanded by Honorius, both of which were Theodosius' sons.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] The situation became more critical in 408, after the death of Stilicho, a general who tried to reunite the Empire and repel barbarian invasion in the early years of the 5th century.
[src:ancient-rome/ancient-rome-p01] In 410, the Theodosian dynasty saw the Visigoths sack Rome.
